neighborhood_overview:
I like our neighbourhood as there is no shortage of things to do ,there is a large Park nearby ,plus loads of restaurants and pubs & supermarkets ,
Everything is available a short walk away ,

The sea and the mountains are not far away and neither is the city it's 6 kilometres away ,all easily accessable
We are in a great location to explore the city & it's environs

I love Dundrum and its surrounding areas ,
There is a huge Shopping Mall 10 mins walk from here with an enormous array of restaurants ranging from Jamie Oliver's to Mexican ,Thai Tapas Bars ,Italian there is a great variety of shops ,Harvey Nicholls ,Michael Kors ,,Hollister ,too many to mention & some good pubs too where you can hear some nice music
There are great transport links nearby ,great access to everywhere we are very near the city 4 miles away ,the mountains are about 8 miles away and the sea is 4 miles , the M50 is just around the corner what's not to like about that ?
There are some lovely villages nearby ,Enniskerry is a lovely little village at the foot of the Dublin mountains & has a beautiful Palladian mansion & gardens worth visiting ,there is a bus locally that will take you there
Ranelagh is noted as a foodie village its about 2 miles from here & has some really good restaurants,
If you want to go to the sea you can take the 75 bus lo
Plenty of buses into the city and the area is pleasant and quiet
Close to the sea, hill walks and the city - via bus and car. It is a quiet neighborhood and my neighbors are friendly too.

Enjoy a walk along the grand canal, or just observe the swans and ducks as they eagerly await some feeding.
Kilmainham Gaol is just a 15 minute walk from our apartment as is the Royal Hospital Kilmainham which hosts the Irish Museum of Modern Art. Take a stroll through the War Memorial Gardens and for those energetic enough, cross over to the Phoenix Park where you can enjoy a hosts of relaxing acitivites or a cycle around the park.

15 minute walk from 'The Dublin', Dublin Discovery Trail,commencing at The Royal Hospital, Kilmainham, Ireland's oldest public building dating back to 1684 and Kilmainham Gaol and Museum. We are a short walk from the War Memorial Gardens and the Phoenix Park. The Liberties with Guinness storehouse is within walking distance or a 5 minute bus ride. Local bus route (No 13, 40, 69 bus) - 1 min Luas tram red line, 5 minute walk. Phoenix Park - 30 mins walk Dublin Zoo - 40 min walk or 5 min bus. Car rental office - Walker Vehicles Rentals Ltd - 10mins Black Lion Pub (one of the best pubs in Dublin) - 3 mins Irish Museum of Modern Art - 15 mins Kilmainham Gaol - 15 mins Guinness Storehouse - 30 mins walk, 5 mins bus. Smithfield - 40 min walk, 10 mins by luas.

Our Portobello neighbourhood is an eternally up and coming area with cool cafes, pubs, restaurants and music venues.   It is a relatively safe and quiet, well-kept residential area within the hub of the city centre with loads of sites and happenings within easy reach.  It is ethnically and economically diverse making for real and dynamic city living.  On our street, you will find a Michelin star restaurant, The Camden Kitchen, plus many wonderful breakfast cafes in the area.  We live next to the old Jewish neighbourhood complete with Bretzel Bakery and the Jewish Heritage Museum.  We are very happy here!

My neighbourhood is very safe, friendly  and old fashioned . The village is Victorian with shops, pubs ,bank,restaurant ,shops it's ten mins walk. The beach  and nature park is across the road , swimming pool and gym  5 mins  away. Best is the neighbours , so kind .
We live in a quiet safe neighbourhood and we are only ten minutes from Dublin airport.
Quiet residential area with good shopping amenities close by.

Our house is located at the gate of the famous Phoenix Park. The house has a beautiful country feel about it but yet it is 10 minutes from the City Centre. We are within 10 mins drive of 5 golf courses, so we are ideal for golf enthusiasts. We are only 20 minutes drive also from the Dublin mountains again ideal for hill walkers,and those that like horse riding.The village of Castleknock is 8 minutes walk from the house. Here you have 5 restaurants 3 pubs and all local amenities like hair dressers, dry cleaners, beauticians etc.
As we are at the Phoenix Park gate, our house is ideally situated for any event being held in the Phoenix park, like Bloom in June, Iron Man in August and motor racing and Dublin Marathon

This street is a beautifully tree lined street which runs right up the the entrance of the Phoenix Park.
This park is the largest urban park in Europe and houses Dublin Zoo and the presidential home and offices as well as a children's playground. It is a wonderful park to visit and spans over 1750 acres.
The street also has beautiful Victorian red bricked houses all along it which date back to the 18th century so it really is a taste of old Dublin.
There is a major supermarket just 3 minutes walk as well as a pharmacy, bakery, coffee shops, bars, restuarants and many other amenities all within easy walking distance.

This street is a beautifully tree lined street which runs right up the the entrance of the Phoenix Park.
This park is the largest urban park in Europe and houses Dublin Zoo and the presidential home and offices as well as a children's playground. It is a wonderful park to visit and spans over 1750 acres.
The street also has beautiful Victorian red bricked houses all along it which date back to the 18th century so it really is a taste of old Dublin.
There is a major supermarket just 2 minutes walk as well as a pharmacy, bakery, coffee shops, bars, restuarants and many other amenities all within easy walking distance.

Conveniently situated close to 'The Dubline' Dublin Discovery Trail, featuring Kilmainham Gaol and Courthouse and The Royal Hospital Kilmainham, Ireland's oldest public building dating back to 1684. We are just a short walk to the War Memorial Gardens. Our apartments have been restored with great care and attention to detail, retaining the original Victorian features providing classic, comfortable and select accommodation in Dublin. Our apartments are upmarket with attention to detail and our guest comfort our priority. Easy access to all the top restaurants, pubs, museums and attractions that Dublin has to offer. For those who prefer a quicker route than the Dubline trail, the bus stop is almost outside the door with route 13 serving Guinness Storehouse, Christchurch Cathedral, Dublin Castle, Temple Bar, Trinity College and O'Connell St.
A 5 minute walk to the Luas red line,travelling via The Museum at Collins Barracks, The Jameson Distillery, Jervis St., Dublin Convention Centre

Portobello is the heart of Dublin 8. The swans congregate along the area of the canal just outside the house. For foodies there are restaurants of all genres within a 10 minute walk. The nightlife along camden street is second to none.

We have lovely neighbours and the location is perfect with access to all the best spots in Dublin and to the main transport systems. It is a real inner city community steeped in history. Make sure to check out the walkway to clontarf where you can walk / cycle beside the sea all the way to bull island - bird sanctuary. If you're feeling brave you can even have a swim here, many do! The local pubs are legendary and some of the best italian food in Dublin is just across the road. There's also lovely deli's all close to hand.

This park is the largest urban park in Europe and houses Dublin Zoo and the presidential home and offices as well as a children's playground. It is a wonderful park to visit and spans over 1750 acres.
The street also has beautiful Victorian red bricked houses all along it which date back to the 18th century so it really is a taste of old Dublin.
There is a major supermarket just 2 minutes walk as well as a pharmacy, bakery, coffee shops, bars, restuarants and many other amenities all within easy walking distance.

A beautiful, historic residential square, built in 1790's, within 5-10 minutes walk of down-town city centre. Elegance and convenience combined with a bit of inner city grittiness. I have loved it all, since 1978!

Mountjoy Square is situated just NE of the historic city centre, within walking distance of just about all the main city attractions. It is the most densely populated area in the entire city: 1500 people have front doors opening onto the Square.

The house fronts onto a 4acre/1.5ha park, across a fairly busy street. This apartment faces the side street, so it is quieter, but you will still hear traffic.....Please bear in mind that this is NOT LEAFY SUBURBIA, but a vibrant, living city community and it's definitely gritty in places... Having said that, I have lived here, uneventfully, for nearly 38 years, and consider the trade-offs well worth it, for the excitement and convenience of having the city on my doorstep..
Pleasant and quiet neighbourhood with shops, restaurants and parks nearby.

A beautiful, historic, residential square, built in 1790's, within 5-10 minutes walk of the city centre. Elegance and convenience combined with a bit of inner city grittiness. I have loved it all, since 1978!
it is a very nice area  and lovely and quiet and I have just installed a downstairs shower room

The Phoenix Park beside and quick and easy access to the centre, its on a charming tree-lined street of three storey Victorian  townhouses (with architectural heritage protection), right beside an enormous park. This my favourite part of central Dublin to live
Lucan village is a quaint place with fun gastro pubs and cafes for tasty breakfast , lunch and dinner all within five minutes walk. Lots of buses go to the city centre from the village.

My neighbourhood is full of history and literary tradition . Very safe to walk around, lovely Beach and park across the road. It's all here, the village is 5 mins away with everything in it , old bars, cafe, restaurants, shops and bank. The city centre is half hour on foot, ten mins by bus , €12 by cab after a night out ,!

A beautiful, historic residential square, built in 1790's, within 5-10 minutes walk of the city centre. Elegance and convenience combined with a bit of inner city grittiness. I have loved it all, since 1978!

Location cannot be better. You are overlooking the River Liffey and directly above the beautiful Ha'penny Bridge. Cross the bridge and you are in Temple Bar with its numerous bars, restaurants, vintage clothes shops, Project Arts Centre, Gallery of Photography, Irish Film Institute and many other attractions.

Dublin two main pedestrian shopping streets, Grafton and Henry St are about 5 minutes away.
Trinity College with its famous Library is 3 minutes walk.

Dublin is experiencing a Renaissance after a long recession and every week a new exciting restaurant, cultural space or play is opening. It is a great time to be visiting!
Just North of the River Liffey, this is the very heart of the city centre and the perfect location for anyone wishing to explore the city by foot. You have everything on your doorstep.

Cafes, pubs, convenience stores, Phoenix Park, view over the river. Handy for city centre -Temple Bar 20 minute walk away, Grafton Street 25 minutes walk, Phoenix Park/Dublin Zoo 10-15 minutes walk. Public transport on the doorstep.

Have a glance at a map of Dublin and you'll see that Dame Street is right in the centre of everything that Dublin has to offer. Trinity College is at one end of Dame Street (3 minute walk from the apartment) and Christ Church Cathedral is at the other (2 minute walk in the other direction). On one side is Dublin Castle and City Hall, and on the other is Temple Bar.

All other notable parts of the city – such as Grafton Street area, St Stephens Green, Merrion Square, O'Connell Street – are within a 10-15 minute walk.

As well as being immersed in Dublin's history and culture, you're surrounded by the best cafes, restaurants, pubs and shopping in Dublin.

The house is located on a quiet street within easy walking distance of the bustle of the restaurants, theatre, and shops of the internationally acclaimed Dundrum Town Centre. For something quieter stroll to the farmers market, gardens, and cafe at the beautiful Airfield Estate. Take a short and pleasant journey by light rail to the center of the city. The station is just across the street. Visible from the house the beautiful Dublin Mountains are a mere 15 min drive away.
The town of Skerries is a very friendly place, as its quite a small resort almost everyone talks to everyone, so its easy to intergrate
The house is located on a quiet one way road with little traffic very close to the main road into the city or towards the airport.

Camden St is a vibrant shopping and socialising street which is one of the main arteries out of the city heading south. The only remaining street except for the famous Moore St. to have fruit and vegetable stalls. A great mix of the traditional and the modern.
We are well serviced with bus routes, bars,, restaurants, take-aways, Botanic Gardens and Glasnevin Cemetary which is No. 2 on Tripadvisor
A country side feel in the city

It is right in the heart of the city centre and yet on a very quiet tree lined street. I like the traditional redbrick fronts of the houses and the fact that you can be in Temple Bar, Grafton Street or St Stephens Green in less than ten minutes. St Patrick's Cathedral and Christchurch and Christchurch Cathedral are minutes away. There is a great selection of traditional pubs and fashionable cafes.

Everything Dublin city centre has to offer is within walking distance.

The Grand Canal Dock area, which is on our doorstep is packed with great restaurants, cute cafes and lively local bars.

There are five great event spaces near my apartment:
1. Bord Gais Energy Theatre - showcases some of the best musicals, opera and ballet in Dublin - is right next to the apartment.
2. The Dublin Convention Centre, which hosts many international conferences & events is directly across the River Liffey from my place (3 minute walk)
3. The 3Arena, a ten minute walk, is a large concert venus will host international acts including Bruno Mars, Aerosmith and Radiohead in 2017
4. Aviva Stadium, home to Irish Rugby & Soccer, is a 20 minute walk along the Grand Canal.
5. Croke Park, the home of our national sports games and also many concerts throughout the summer like Bruce Springstein, Beyonce & Take That, is a 25 minute walk from our place.

The Grand Canal Dock area, which is on our doorstep is packed with great restaurants, cute cafes and lively local bars.

Inchicore is one of the more historical neighbourhoods in Dublin. Kilmainham Gaol, Richmond Barracks and the Royal Hospital Kilmainham (IMMA) are within a kilometre of the house.  This is a quiet area with helpful and friendly neighbours, easy to access the city centre by LUAS (tram) or Dublin Bikes (free bike scheme).  The Phoenix Park and War Memorial Gardens are within walking distance.

My home is located in a lovely, peaceful and exclusive neighbourhood called Dartry. I feel very lucky to live there, as it's away from the rush and noise of the city, yet so well connected that you're there in 10 minutes when you want to be!

-- There is a great pub/restaurant around the corner, which is the heart of the neighbourhood. It's called The Dropping Well- it's a real Irish "local" and is very popular. Some people argue it has the best Guinness in Dublin!

-- There are lots more pubs, restaurants and shops within a short walk or tram ride of the house. Ranelagh village is only a few minutes away and is very popular amongst us locals for its fantastic pub and restaurant scene. Dundrum Town Centre is a few minutes the other direction and has a huge shopping centre and lots of excellent restaurants.

-- The city centre is within very easy reach, exactly 10 mins by Luas [tram], and my house is also very convenient for getting to places suc
Its nice and quiet yet near to the city center.

We waited for a house to become available in this Phibsboro neighbourhood because we knew how much families loved to bring up kids here. The community spirit in Shandon help drive the annual street party with kids sports and a giant banquet, the Christmas carol singing around the streets, Halloween festivities, and the local Phizzfest. The Royal Canal passes only minutes away and is ideal for a jog, a stroll or a bike ride. A range of small independent shops are ten minutes walk away- great deli & gift store, fruit & veg store, fine butcher and fishmonger and a large supermarket ten minutes the other direction. Within 20 minutes you can walk to Dublin City centre and  the National Botanic Gardens- one of Dublin's treasures and Glasnevin Cemetery and Museum. Thirty minutes walk brings you to Phoenix Park (the biggest urban park in Europe) and Dublin zoo. The house provides easy access to numerous museums and galleries, including Collins Barracks or the Museum of Modern Art. The Gravedig
Safe, family friendly

Kimmage is one of the oldest parts of Dublin city and has a great community vibe going on. It combines the traditional with the modern which I like.  There are several historical sites to see and two Public Parks.  There is also a Shopping Centre nearby

Phibsborough (also spelled Phibsboro) is very convenient in that it is near to all amenities, e.g. shops, cafes and public transport. It is also within easy access to the centre of the City, so guests can choose to avail of the tranquility of their apartment or the busy nightlife of the city.
Convenient to Croke Park, The Botanic Gardens, The Phoenix Park and Glasnevin Museum. Also within easy reach of the Gate Theatre, Dublin Writers' Museum and other attractions.
It's even easier to get to the city centre now, using the newly opened Luas tram line. Only 4 stops to O'Connell Street!

In vibrant Stonybatter, beside a former convent where Robin Hood's pal, Little John lived.
Academic quarter: TUD college campus 200m; The Law Society Solicitors school 400m; The King's Inns Barrister Law school 400m.
History: Saint Michan's Church Crypts 400m. GUINNESS storehouse 800m. Jameson Whiskey museum 300m. Collins Barracks museum 600m.

Our house is a detached house down a country-style laneway with just 5 other houses. We are approx 20 mins from the city with plenty of shops / cafes within walking distance as well as the Phoenix Park too.

Dundrum is one of the best neighbourhoods in south Dublin. We have fantastic amenities closeby in the form of the Dundrum Town Centre with lots of great restaurants and shopping facilities. Transport to the city is close by in the form of our tram systems (LUAS) which is close, convenient and very reliable. We are also close to the beautiful Marley Park with hundreds of acres of woodland. Wicklow is a short drive away with easy access to all of the major attractions including Glendalough and Avoca. The house is accessed from the M50 motorway which has a direct link to Dublin Airport - journey by car to the house from the airport is about 25 minutes.

We are in the middle of nowhere... 2 miles from nearest village, with a local pub, shop, hair dresser and church... we have the famous 'Seamus Ennis' centre that host concerts, films and trad sessions.

Despite being really close to the city centre it is a nice and peaceful area close to a few parks, decent supermarkets and gorgeous places for brunch and lunch. Amazing Italian restaurant which is right beside the best pub in Dublin for a Guinness is only 10/15 min walk away. Also really handy to and from the airport. 12 min taxi ride through the port tunnel :-)

There is a bus stop at the end of my toad and the tram (Luas) is a few minutes walk away. Stop is Spencer Dock.

The neighbours are lovely too!

Ringsend/ Irishtown is a quiet yet vibrant suburban neighbourhood, just outside Dublin city centre. We have a great selection of pubs and restaurants on our doorstep while still within walking distance to the city centre. If you're staying in Dublin for a concert in The 3 Arena, a rugby or football match in the Aviva Stadium or a musical show in the Bord Gais Energy Theatre, we are perfectly located for all three. Other amenties close by include for Sandymount beach for walking or jogging.

The famous Phoenix Park (the largest urban park in Europe)  is just a few steps from the front door. The Park won top prize in the International Urban Parks Awards 2018. The Dublin Zoo is within about 300 meters and you can sometimes hear the lions and the monkeys from the back garden!

The area of Dublin 8 is a local neighbourhood, near the city Centre. It is a residential area with a lidl supermarket, cafe, launderette, hairdresser and a pharmacy close by.
A ten minute walk will get you to some good bars and cafes, and a street for antiques, and a 10 minute bus, or 25 minute walk will get you into the heart of the city centre , with bars, restaurants, music, etc. Trinity College is another 5 mins.
Dublin city centre is relatively small so everything is very close and walkable. The bus is a minute away and the Luas (tram) is 8 minutes away fron the house.
We've compiled a list of places we like to go and a map for you to take away, bars, restaurants, etc, as well as a selection of touristy things if you'd prefer. The Guinness Brewery is a few minutes walk away ( you can see the bar at the top from our kitchen), Teelings Whiskey distillery, Christchurch and St.Patricks Cathedrals are 10-20 minutes walk away, and downtown bars and restaurants about 25 m

Blackrock and Monkstown are fabulous villages by the sea. The house is less than 10 minutes walk from either village villages both with great restaurants, pubs and shops. I have compiled a useful folder with local information on where best to eat, shop, interesting attractions etc. The seafront at Seapoint is a great spot for a dip! This is a safe, secure well established neighbourhood. I will leave a list of recommended activities for guests.

Directly on bustling food emporium Capel St, around the corner from the shopping streets of Henry & Mary St, whilst a 2 mins across the Liffey from Temple Bar, Dublin Castle, Dame St, George's St and Grafton. You literally are in the centre of everything a Dublin City traveller can ask for. Nearby Pubs (+LGBT), Restaurants, Coffee Shops, 24 Hour Shops, Gyms, Cinemas and Shopping Centres.
The neighbourhood is very central with easy access to the city centre as well as Hannover quay and the IFSC financial district.
Great Location - close to great restaurants e.g. Paulies Pizza - very modern and new round building. Conveniently located just a 3 min stroll from the DART Trainstation and Spar Market.

5 km from city centre. Plenty of small shops, bank, post office, hairdressers, barbers, take away restaurants and pharmacies 2 minutes from house.
Brickfield and Sundrive Parks within 5 minute walk from house.

Our neighbourgh hood is extremely central and near all amenities (Dublin Bus, LUAS Tramline, DART Station and Connolly Train station, Shopping center, Grocery stores, the Spire, High street, O'Connell street...etc).

You will be within walking distance to the best pubs and restaurant of Dublin.
We are just a few minutes away from Temple Bar, the renouned O'Connell street, the fancy high street of Grafton !

There are so many great things about Bray, it is know as the Gateway to the Garden of Ireland and is nestled between the Wicklow / Dublin mountains and the sea. There are so many great walks and hikes, there is a vibrant cultural & music scene along with great restaurants and pubs including the fantastic Harbour Bar (voted best Bar in the World off the beaten track, Lonely Planet Guide 2010) Guest frequently comment on how friendly people in Bray are.

The Mill is in a peaceful, tree lined setting by the river but ideally situated in the centre of Bray down small private road. It's only a couple of minutes walk to coffee shops, restaurants, a great super market (SuperValu) and just over 5 mins walk to the beach, the promenade, the award winning Platform Pizza, Harbour Bar and so many other great places.

The Cliff Walk is stunning and takes around two hours, there is an abundance of wildlife, flowers & fauna, including seals, a huge variety of birds and if you ar
Convenience shops only 5 minutes walk.

A 6 minute walk to Dublin Castle, along the river, the apartment is city center yet quiet plus just a 5 minute walk to the famous Guinness Store House.

Dublin's famous Smithfield square is literally across the river facing the apartment. There are a number of very trendy, good value restaurants with amazing food 2 minutes away on Benburb St. The art house cinema "The Light House" is across the street also on the square

Our neighbourhood is traditionally working-class and in recent years it has become an area of urban regeneration. This is still ongoing and the neighbourhood remains very mixed with lots of 'inner city Dublin' to appreciate.

Every month new amenities (cafes, shops etc) are opening and the neighbourhood is transforming but it is important to know that this is not one of Dublin's well-established middle-class neighbourhoods. This is reflected in our price.

We can provide you with a list of local cafes, markets etc so you can explore this dynamic area and you are a 25 minute walk or a short bus ride from the hustle and bustle of Dublin's city centre.

We have lived in our area since 1977, and in our present house since 1994.  We are in the heart of the city, and yet in a vibrant residential area, with houses of architectural interest built between 1838 and 1895, with some modern pieces of course as well.  We are a few minutes' walk from two beautiful parks, St. Stephen's Green and the Iveagh Gardens, and also close to the Grand Canal with its cycleway all the way to the Bord Gais Theatre and Google and Facebook headquarters.  Whelans and The Village music venues are at the end of our street, so that end of the street can be fairly lively, especially at the week-ends.

Crumlin is an historic village on the road leading westward out of Dublin -- as a result, the public transportation into the city is easy and fast.

Situated within walking distance of 3 major hospitals: Children's hospital, St. James' hospital and the Coombe Women's hospital.

We live in a quiet cul-de-sac. Although it is only a block from a major road, you can't hear the traffic -- instead, you hear birds singing from the rooftops of the houses on our street.

Down the street, the Old County Road runs parallel to the main road and contains shops, fish-and-chippers, takeaways, and there are two cafes serving good coffee and sandwiches. Sheary's pub has an inviting atmosphere, serve delicious pizzas and has live music on weekends.

Getting around

-Excellent, regular bus route going into the city and beyond, a 2 minute walk.
-The Luas (red tram line) is a 10 minute walk.
-Taxi to airport costs €25.

This bedroom is at the front of the house so, particularly at week-ends, you may hear some on-street talking at night-time.
You will be right beside St Patrick's Cathedral, and only a few minutes walk from Christchurch, Trinity College, Stephen's Green and the heart of Dublin city.

The ease of access to downtown Dublin, combined with having the sea and some beautiful parks on the doorstep makes this a very attractive location. We're a bus ride to Howth and we're close to Croke Park, the Aviva stadium, 3 Arena, Bord Gais Energy Theatre, the national Cricket grounds as well as Dublin's other theatres and the many attractions the city centre has to offer.
Clontarf is a quiet sea-side village with shops, bars and restaurants and the village is just ten minutes outside the city

I love that it's quiet & peaceful yet a 20 mins walk from the centre of town.
You would not know you are in the city, but you are

The street also has beautiful Victorian red bricked houses all along it which date back to the 18th century so it really is a taste of old Dublin.

its a quiet neighbourhood and on bus routes to city centre, blanchardstown shopping centre. autobhn pub is 5 mins walk and has meals from 12 noon until 9pm and in drumcondra area lots of good restaurants 10 mins by car!

Its just about the best place to live in Dublin. Everything is on your doorstep, including lovely restaurants, lively pubs, barista cafes, and only 20 mins walk through Georgian Dublin to St. Stephens Green, which is the main pedestrianised shopping area on the south side of the city and River Liffey.

Location, location, location! Bachelors Walk is a very lively city centre location with lots of shops, restaurants, cafes, bars & night-life right outside your door! If you don't mind the hustle & bustle associated with city centre living then this is the perfect spot to get to visit and experience the many sights and sounds of Dublin. Many of the cities top shops, nightclubs and live music venues are only a minute's walk away. And if you want to take a trip to the countless coastal & inland sights, easy access to public transport is right on your doorstep too. It is also ideal for overnight stays for concerts & events at the 3 Arena, Convention Centre or Croke Park stadium as all are either in walking distance or on a direct link via the Luas tram system. As I mention already the apartment is situated in a very busy city centre location - the benefits of its central location and proximity to the shops & night life have to be weighed up with the potential for noise, especially on publi
Apartment is right beside St Stephens Green and in city centre.

Ranelagh is a very popular enclave in Dublin these days, it is so close to the City Centre whilst having a village identity all of it own.
It is full of all amenities you could need and you are just off the main street.

We live in historic Georgian Dublin. The house itself was built in the 1800's and still maintains many original features, with a modern twist.

The area is really charming just outside the city center. Just across the street there is a deli, Starbucks, convenience store, restaurants and traditional Irish pubs! There are also local parks and a canal with a nice walk on our street.

Santry is typical and Urban area. Lots of green space.
Walking distance to: food store Super Valu open late, restaurants and fish&chips open late Macari’s.
Leasure centre, theathere and famous Rediscover Centre are also here here. Check them online.

Camden St is a vibrant shopping and socialising street which is one of the main arteries out of the city heading south. The only remaining street except for the famous Moore St. to have fruit and vegetable stalls. A great mix of the traditional and the modern.
Bray seafront is only a 5 minute walk with its lovely pebble beach and loads of pubs and resturants.

You have Smock Ally Theatre on the same street if interested in theatre.
Bakery is around the corner for your breakfast. Or if you don't feel like making your own coffee there are plenty of small and extremely nice coffee shops beside you.
On West Essex Street and Cows Lane there are a lot of small shops that are not to be missed.

The Santry and Whitehall neighborhood is safe and accessible by public transport. 2.60 Euro by bus to the city centre. Omni SC is less than 5 minutes walking distance, Other attractions within walking distance is Dublin City University, The Helix Concert Hall, National Botanical Gardens and the historical Glasnevin Cemetery with its award winning Museum. The world famous Croke Park Stadium  the home of Gaelic Football and Hurling is just down the road. Croke Park. There are several fitness centres, swimming pools  and Morton Stadium for the more serious athletes within walking distance.

The house is situated at the edge of the bohemian Camden Street/Wexford Street and Portobello area but is also considered as 'South Inner-City' where most of the Dublin nightlife is. Synge Street is less than 10 minutes walking distance from Dublin's main shopping and restaurant district and cultural quarter surrounding Grafton Street.
Although only one block from the main street, Synge Street is surprisingly tranquil day and night.
Our neighbourhood is very central but offers a vibrant alternative to the regular Dublin tourist traps even though Temple Bar is a mere 15 minute walk away.

The Santry and Whitehall neighborhood is safe and accessible by public transport. 2.60 Euro by bus to the city centre. Ranelagh still retains its character as a village even though it is only minutes away from the centre of Dublin. It has a long history including being the location of ancient battles and of the first hot air balloon flight in Ireland. In 1785, only two years after the first manned flight, Richard Crosbie was the first Irishman to make a manned flight when he successfully flew in a hot air balloon from Ranelagh Gardens to Clontarf. Padraig Pearse, one of the leaders of the Easter Rising in 1916, established St . Enda's school on September 8, 1908, in Cullenswood House, Ranelagh. All the major Easter Rising locations in the city centre can easily be reached.
There are over 30 restaurants, coffee shops and pubs in Ranelagh should you not want to go as far as the city.

Situated in a prime and highly sought after location in the heart of Drumcondra Village there is a host of local amenities and services on the doorstep including an excellent selection of shops, restaurants, cafes, boutiques including Griffith Park and the Botanic Gardens.
Everything.  So close to town, with lots of lovely restaurants and cafes and all the amenities.

Templemore Avenue is at the heart of a sought-after historic residential area. A short walk in either direction reaches two villages full of gourmet shops, bars, and restaurants. It's also a 25 min walk or short bus ride to the famous Temple Bar and Trinity College
Typical Irish Pub located around the Apartment, Full of tourist Activities but also quiet place to relax.

Our area is an old Dublin neighbourhood with a great community spirit. Here you will find friendly and helpful neighbours, all too willing to assist and stop for a friendly chat. We have one of Dublin's oldest pubs "The Black Lion" where you can enjoy an open fire, decent pub food, and good company. There are restaurants, coffee shops, supermarkets, and pharmacies within a few minute's walk.  Rascals Brewery and Pizzeria is across the street, where brewery tours are available.  For culture and history, visit Richmond Barracks, Kilmainham Gaol, and The Irish Museum of Modern Art, all within a 15-minute walk.  Dublin's oldest cemetery at Goldenbridge is 5 minutes walk.  For outdoor relaxation, a walk to the War Memorial Gardens is highly recommended and from there one can cross over to the Phoenix Park.

We live on a quiet street, 7 minutes walk from Rathmines which has almost everything you might need - five supermarkets, two cinemas, a swimming pool, two bookshops,  lots of restaurants and cafes... We are 15 minutes by bus from the city centre.

The house is located in Dublin 8 in a neighborhood of mostly period redbrick homes.  We have two fabulous cafes in the area, Noshingtons and Fumbally.  And there's a terrific new little Italian restaurant (Rottinculo) just a few minutes walk away, on Clanbrassil Street.   Walk 10 minutes East through Portobello and you're on Camden Street, which is one of Dublin's hidden gems, with a lovely collection of cafes and specialty food shops, as well as one of Dublin's best health food stores.   It's just a 15-20 minute (1 mile; 1.6 kilometers) walk to St. Stephen's Green and a 25-30 minute (1.8 miles; 3 kilometers) walk to Trinity College.

Ranelagh is a residential area and urban village. It is in the postal district of Dublin 6. This apartment is centred within the heart of Ranelagh Village. Pubs, restaurants and a friendly, lively local atmosphere make Ranelagh a wonderful place to stay and relax.

Skerries is a beautiful part of the world and a great place to stay while visiting Dublin only 40minutes on the train into the city but far enough away to enjoy the tranquility of Ireland. Skerries coastline is beautiful with a lovely fishing harbour and a few beaches to choose from.
Skerries Harbour is hugely popular when the weather is any way good, with many great restaurants and bars.

For more information on the local area you should look up the article recently appearing in the Irish Independent titled :
Reasons why you should consider moving to Skerries by the seaside

Restaurants & pubs nearby - Sandymount village is a 15 or 20  min walk along the beach promenade and a 15 min bus or train (Dart) ride to the city centre, with lots of busses and trains  running to city centre. The village - at its centre is a small public park which teems with families and people on a sunny day and surrounded by lots of restaurants -  Buju Burger, Pete's American Diner, Dunne & Crezenzi Italian, Mario's Italian Pizzeria and Bistro, Indie Spice, Browne's Deli, Butlers Pantry & Coffee, Cafe Java,  lots of nice bars, a Tesco supermarket, some clothing boutiques and shoe shops, an optician, a couple of pharmacies and a Mace for bus and train tickets, mobile top up etc.    It's also only a 5 minute walk from the beach where you can access  some beautiful nature trails alongside the beach,  one of which is a 10 mile trek out to Poolbeg Lighthouse - an absolute must for nature lovers and walker
Excellant location, in the heart of Dublin and only minutes walk to all of the main attractions.

Great neighbourhood in trendy area only minutes from local amenities. 5 min walk to St Patrick's Cathedral, 10 min walk to Wexford Street / Georges Street / Camden Street, home to Dublin's best bars and restaurants ( I will provide a list of places to eat and drink). 4 min walk to the famous 'Fumbally Cafe', Dublin's best coffee shop.

Located beside grand canal in very quiet safe area. Along the canal is very picturesque. A family friendly quiet neighborhood. No load roads besides the house. The property is located in a cul de sac.

Clontarf is such a great location in Dublin for so many reasons.  It is the place Dubliners come to when they want to walk along the seafront, have a coffee and ice-cream and dine in the restaurants. City centre, very close to great restaurants, coffee shops and bars, in the heart of the old North city. Also very close to top tourist sites like Guinness storehouse and Jameson distillery. A 10 minute walk to Temple Bar.
Walking distance for top attraction of Dublin, also very nice building and appartament.
Great location with Dublin city, Croke Park and a host of bars/restaurants and attractions on your doorstep.

Our neighborhood is friendly and safe. There is a playground, shop, cafe, walking tracks and a duck pond within a five minute walk. You can walk from our house, through the neighboring estate, across the road and straight up the mountain to the Blue Light Pub, famous for its views.

Portmarnock and surrounding area is a fantastic Dublin seaside location. Pubs, restaurants, shops, beautiful Portmarnock Beach (the famous 'Velvet Strand) all within walking distance.

Leisure centre with pool and gym facilities in Portmarnock village. Beautiful Portmarnock Malahide coastal walk is recommended- then get the bus or train back. Tennis court & free underground parking on site.

Lennox Street is situated in the heart of Old Portobello. This is what 'VisitDublin' says about the neighbourhood :-

"Portobello runs along the edge of Dublin’s picturesque Grand Canal bridging the gap between Rathmines and the popular Camden Street area. When the sun is out the waterside plays host to many relaxing lunches and post-work drinks with crowds stretching from The Barge to The Portobello and beyond.

Dublin’s old Jewish Quarter is café territory, with top tea experts Wall & Keogh, the beautiful BiBi’s (attached to an equally special boutique, Dolls), the wholesome Nelly’s, traditional bagel-makers the Bretzel and sweet-tooth ticklers the Cake Café all finding their homes in its maze of streets.

Its restaurant scene is equally as busy. Locks Brasserie is one of the most highly-regarded fine dining restaurants in the city. Rotana Café serves some of the best falafel in town and also offer flavoured Shisha pipes for those who want to try some

There are street parties, harvest festivals and various goings on.  We live in a cul de sac and, much like their grandparents probably, the children play on the street most of the day. Being a five minute train ride from Dublin's city centre is also a bonus for access to shops, galleries and theatres.

Temple Bar is the most vibrant, exciting neighborhood in Dublin's city centre. A warren of medieval, cobble-stoned streets, it's officially Dublin's Cultural Quarter and houses dozens of art and culture organisations and institutes. It's also the heart of Dublin's social life... more cafes, bars, restaurants than anyone needs!

30 minutes drive from the city centre and 5 minutes to the sea. Close to all transport systems, the 46A bus stops outside the development. The local gastro-pub is a 10 minutes walk and there is a small shopping centre with a Tesco and Boots across the road. There is a beautiful park within the development and the villages of Dun Laoghaire, Monkstown, Glasthule and Dalkey are very close by. There are lots of fantastic restaurants and pubs in the area and magnificent scenery for walks and Dun Laoghaire, Dalkey and the surrounding areas are well known for their many festivals that take place throughout the year.
There is a beautiful beach nearby called Sandycove which is only 10 minutes drive and the house is also not far from the N11 motorway to Wicklow and Wexford.
Financial district, which means a really safe, city centre neighborhood and quiet as a mouse after office hours.
So much on our doorstep….a browse in Hen’s Teeth, brunch in Two Pups, a pint of Guinness in Fallon’s pub, listening to the bells in St. Patrick’s Cathedral Park.
Vibrant city centre spot close to all amenities and attractions.

The best fish and chips in Ireland is up the street called burdocks a must do.
If for nothing more than to look at the wall of fame , rock stars moves stars and even President's have stopped to buy the fish and chips. around the corner to the right you will find a cute hole in the wall called Fallens Pub. Across the street is the spar shop , you can get breakfast rolls and sandwiches all day . Remember you must be quite and live on both sides of me !

Clontarf village is one of the oldest villages in the leafy suburbs of North Dublin.  It was at one time a small fishing village but is now a tranquil neighbourhood with cosmopolitan village hosting a blend of cafes, bars and restaurants.  Take a stroll on the promenade and along the wooden bridge down to the Stella Maris one mile right out into the bay.  Alternatively take a walk in nearby St. Anne's Park  once the seat of the Jameson (Whiskey) family.  Beside the sea and away from the hustle and bustle of the city but only a short distance to be right in the heart of it.

A quiet cul de sac off one of Dublin's beautiful tree lined residential streets. A minutes walk to Bibi's cafe and Fumbally. Five minutes walk to bustling Camden street, famous for live music, restaurants and night life. Ten minutes walk to Grafton street and St Stephen's green and fifteen minutes walk to Trinity in one direction and Guinness store house in another.

One of the most sought after areas in Dublin. Room is overlooking the Liffey with all the bars and restaurants of Grand Canal Basin only a few minutes away. Close to major tech companies, consulting firms and investment firms. Energy Theatre, 3 Arena and Dublin Convention Centre a few minutes walk away.
Lovely area,great locations to Shopping Center, Phoenix park, City center. There are local parks,shops and pubs.

Our neighbourhood is very quiet and tight knit  but it's right on the edge of the city centre. You can walk to Stephen's Green in 20 minutes. There's plenty of corner shops and supermarkets in walking distance. We've a park up the road with tennis courts, a basketball court and plenty of green space. The access to the M50 is only a few minutes drive away which means that if you want to get out of the city, it's easily done. A day trip to the countryside or seaside can be done without any hassle and we'd highly recommend it!

This is a relatively quiet street, especially at night. We are close to Sundrive Road park which has tennis courts, a basket ball court, football pitch and cycling, running, walking are all recommended here.
At the end of our street there are some small convenience shops, Pharmacies, fresh fruit & veg shop, etc. There are supermarkets 5-10 mins walk away.
There are two restaurants close by and plenty of takeaways.
5 min drive from us on route into the city there are two organic markets side by side off Cork Street and between them they are open Thu-Sun. On the last Sunday of the month on the same street there is the Dublin Flea Market. All well worth a visit.
We are also very close to the Grand Canal which is one of two canals nearly encircling Dublin's inner city and makes for a lovely walk into the city.
Near to the city centre, the Botanic Gardens, Croke Park, Beaches and Parks, Airport, hotels , pubs, night life, shops etc etc

Safe, relaxing and quiet neighborhood.
Public transports are closeby: the tramway from Dublin city centre will take you to the apartment in 25 mins + 13 mins walk.

We are lucky enough to be surrounded by plenty of natures finest offerings including the Phoenix Park whilst also being in very close proximity to the city life if that's more your thing. The Phoenix Park is home to Dublin Zoo, Irelands President, the American Ambassador to Ireland as well as numerous deer! It is also the largest walled garden in Europe and is the ideal spot for many activities (bikes can be hired in the park) or the more relaxed picnics!

If you prefer some local shopping Blanchardstown Retail Park with all the top stores is only minutes away as is the idyllic village of Castleknock with a variety of restaurants, boutiques & cafés.

Dublin Airport is a stones throw away at 10miles which makes us an ideal stopover for your travels! And the city centre is 10km away & can be accessed via bus and train.

Our extended family have been in this much loved suburb on a hill in North Dublin for 3 generations. It is friendly, safe, green neighbourhood, full of character. There are great local pubs & cafes and a bus stop 2 minutes from our house with a direct route to the city centre. DCU university, fabulous Botanic Gardens, historic Glasnevin Cemetery, Croke Park stadium and Jameson distillery are all very close too. Plenty of parks with playgrounds nearby or you may like to cycle to the sea-front? We have 3 adult bikes & it takes 20-30mins.

My apartment block has 2 entrances, one from the historic Georgian street which will bring you directly to the James Joyce museum and cute cafes on this late 18th century row of houses. The other leads you out to a playground and small park around the corner.

Located in a well established suburb of South Dublin, at the foothills of the Dublin mountains. Approx. 20mins drive outside the city centre. Plenty of access to public transport within a 3 min walk. If you have your own car, there is plenty of free safe car parking at the property.
Local supermarket located just at the end of the street, with a pharmacy, hair & beauty salon and hardware store, all in the shopping complex. Also within the locality there are numerous restaurants and take aways. There are some beautiful large parks nearby, ideal for walks and with lovely amenities for children.
For the outdoor enthusiasts our property location facilitates easy access to beautiful areas such as Enniskerry, Powerscourt Gardens & Waterfalls, Glendalough, Wicklow, Howth and Malahide, the Dublin Mountains and a number of convenient beaches.
For the golfers among you, Ireland is renowned for its fabulous golf courses. There are a number of these within a 20 min drive of our prop
Our home is 3.5 km from the city centre with a spacious garden and close to parks. All amenities are close by. We have listed these amenities in the guidebook.
Always something to do or see

In the heart of Dalkey, a Heritage Town in South County Dublin just ten miles south of Dublin city, half an hour by train.
A warm village atmosphere with castle, Killiney Hill, Coliemore Harbour and an abundance of fantastic bars & restaurants.

This is a very lively place when there is a football match or a concert in nearby croke Park. U2, the rolling stones, Ed sheeran to mention but a few. There are plenty of bars Fagans, Kennedys, grocery stores Tesco centra. Restaurants,  independent pizza, Fagans and Kennedys also do food.
Shops 1 min. walk. Excellent access to city centre & East coast.

Our neighbourhood is considered one of the top home locations in Dublin. We enjoy a great number of excellent restaurants, bars and deli's within walking distance (booking during horse show is essential). Despite having all this all this close by, our square is very quiet and peaceful and is very much a family neighbourhood. We are a short 10 minute stroll from the RDS along the leafy banks of the Doddar and parking outside the house is free. To give you an idea of the neighbourhood, below are some of the restaurants within a 5 minute walk, all excellent and highly recommended in magazine reviews. You can check them out on line.

Portobello is an eclectic and historic neighbourhood with stunning canal walks and great cafes for brunch, ethnic cuisine and pubs. It is a 15/20 min stroll to the city centre but it would be a shame to miss out on all this neighbourhood has to offer. On Camden St. there is a multitude of award winning restaurants and bars to choose from as well as Whelans, a fantastic live music venue. Beside the house there is a cafe which is open late and do great Thai food and a fantastic Indian restaurant. If you like fine dining, Within two minutes walk of the cottage is Locks Brasserie, a beautiful restaurant over looking the canal and other new contemporary Irish restaurants called Bastible and Clanbrassil House. Also not to be missed is Gaillot & Gray, a French pizzeria that is a bakery in the morning for fresh sourdough and pastries. Across from the cottage is the MVP bar. A cosy pub which does great cocktails. The Jewish Museum is also located in Portobello and on the weekends there is canal
The neighbourhood is in the North side of Dublin not far from the river and central shopping area of Dublin (Henry Street). There is a lively Chinatown and many theatres/bars five minutes away also.
Small village a corner shop with supplies , small butcher , best fruit and veg shop and also nice friendly local pub called the step inn

Wonderful quiet established neighborhood and only 15mins to Dublin Airport
Bank, post office, supermarkets, pharmacies, dry cleaners and coffee shop are 5 min walk. 30 seconds walk to the bus stop to the city centre
We are a mere 5km from Dublin City Centre. 3km from the National Botanical Gardens of Ireland, famous for the exquisitely restored historic glasshouses and 3kms from Glasnevin Cemetery, which this year received the Trip Advisor 2018 Traveller's Choice award.

The loft is in Mountjoy Square, a vibrant area close to the historic city centre and within walking distance to main attractions. Grocery stores and breakfast places are just around the corner. Local restaurants are nearby, as well as Chinatown and pubs.
Plenty of restaurants, supermarkets, pubs within 5 minutes walk. Area is useful for late arriving guests.
Quite, friendly and close to public transport

We are located in a quiet neighborhood in the South Dublin suburbs. Our location gives you easy access to Dublin city but also some beautiful towns and villages like Dun Laoighaire and Dalkey and of course, the garden county, Wicklow for anyone looking for amazing scenery. Close to public parks, gyms, golf courses, mountain biking/hiking, horse riding, sailing, shopping ... the list goes on and on.

The apartment is located on the ground floor of the building, Christchurch and Dublinia are less than 5 minutes walk and it will take you about 10 minutes max to get to Temple Bar and City Hall. If you walk in the opposite direction, you will find yourselves in front of the Guinness Store House within 10 minutes.

There is a library with a gym and many other amenities close by, such as Chinese, Indian and Italian take away, a very famous ice cream place, where you can enjoy the best ice creams ever.

Swords village can be reached only 10 minutes by bus on the 33B. The bus stop is within walking distance from home (5-7 minutes). It stops in the heart of the village, where there are even more amenities to enjoy. From the Swords village, within 5 minutes walking there is a big shopping centre (Pavilions), where there are many shops and cinemas, which can also be reached on the bus.

Also Malahide village can be reached 5 minutes by train, where you can enjoy many boutiques, coffee shops, the marina, etc, a must see place! Another great place to enjoy the evening is Skerries, which can also be reached on the train, 10-15 minutes from Donabate.

Just in Donabate you can enjoy, the Newbridge Demesne, which opened as a County Dublin Regional Park in 1986. It consists of a

This little gem of a flat is hidden in one of Dublin's most well-known, urban villages. The location is perfect for those seeking a calmer environment than the city centre; however also having a bit of life. With the main street bustling with bars and fabulous restaurants it attracts many people of all ages day through to night time. As well as this, it is just on the cusp of town and is easy access for taxis and all other public transport.

Only 5-10 min from retail park for all you need: coffee shops, post office, food shopping , pharmacy and local clinic etc.
Howth village and Malahide is very popular destinations for tourists. It is only 5 min by train or 30 min walk from our place to Howth and there is direct bus to Malahide Village.
Centrally located and within walking distance of Grand Canal Dock, Temple Bar, Dawson Street, Grafton Street and Henry Street.

This is a very central area, especially at night.
I am close to Grafton Street and located among the best restaurants and nightclubs, Lots shops like Tesco, Centra, Pharmacies, Veg shop etc..
Park Court is a turning off Park Avenue in Sandymount, is a quiet residential area with a small green with tall oak trees on it.  It is a safe and friendly place.

We are situated in a coastal town called Rush . We 're close to Skerries . Cashpoint, pubs, music, restaurants, library, supermarkets are here.Rush is a farming agricultural town on the seas edge . Horse riding, boat trips, massage . Beautiful coastline for lovely walks, chilled semi rural feel, yet close to vibrancy of Dublin city when you want to go Downtown.
A good friend living close by is an excellent massage therapist( hot stone, deep tissue massage) if you would like a body rescue please let me know and I will pass details on so you can talk to her to see if you're interested.
Quiet residential area but access to pubs, restaurants , a few minutes walk away, clubs, city centre, galleries, theatres a short drive away. Beach and park walk a few minutes away from house.

A quiet residential area which is outside of the city centre but it is easy to get to and from by walking or public transport.

All within a short walk there are cafes, bars an restaurants, I've mentioned some of them in my guidebook and can tell you about more when you're here 🤗

The apartment building is right next to Grand Canal Dock, a lively and modern area of the city, close to the Bord Gais Theatre, the Aviva Stadium, and the 3 Arena. The IFSC is right across the river, and the apartment affords a view of it.

Five minutes walk to Rathmines and Ranelagh Villages, where you will find supermarkets, cafes, restaurants, boutiques, cinema, gym, taxi's and both bus and luas (tram) stations to the city centre.
Alternatively, the city centre, Temple Bar and St Stephen's Green are an easy 20 minute walk.
Belgrave Square has a childrens playground and is a 5 minute walk away.
The neighbourhood is quiet, in the apartment complex you'll find working professionals. Marks & Spencer supermarket downstairs as well as the Spar. Many nice little cafes and pubs around the square.

The apartment is well situated in the city centre, to the right a few minutes walk is the Guinness Storehouse and to the left Christchurch Cathedral and Temple Bar. Thomas Street with all its old pubs and local shops are around the corner. The Brazen Head pub one of the oldest in Dublin is a couple of minutes walk away. Food is served here and Irish music played.

Cabra is an ideal base to explore Dublin city with many landmarks a short distance away, from Croke Park, to Stephen's Green, and Phoenix Park.

The airport is c. 20 minutes by taxi.

With local coffee shops a short stroll to start your day while access to the city centre attractions is within easy reach with our excellent Luas and Dublin bus links.
We live on a quiet road beside a lovely park. We are very close to the village of Swords, only 10 minute walk. there are lots of lovely restaurants, pubs and shops.
We have a beautiful park outside our house, we live on a nice quiet road.

The neighborhood is a trendy area just north of the river Liffey, very central but still quiet and peaceful.
The apartment is surrounded by many city attractions, supermarkets, pubs, restaurants, cinemas.
The main shopping areas are just 10/15 minutes walking as well as Phoenix Park, Temple Bar.
You will find more information in the Guidebook but feel free to ask if you need additional info.

We are located very close to Dublin airport which is convenient for any people travelling from abroad. We are quite close to the Botanic Gardens and DCU college where there is a beautiful park. Bus journey to city centre isn't too far either.

Our luxury Dublin suites are located in the heart of the city centre, just around the corner from the National Concert Hall and beautiful St Stephens Green.

Premier Suites Dublin Leeson Street is only minutes walking from fashionable shopping on Grafton Street and attractions including Trinity College, the National Gallery and Georgian Dublin are on our doorstep. For sports enthusiasts we are centrally located with Croke Park, O2 Arena, Aviva Stadium at Lansdowne Road, and the RDS all easy to get to.

Very central , one minute from St Patrick cathedral ,2 mins from
Christchurch cathedral , 5 mins from Temple Bar and 10 mins from Trinity and Guinness Store House

Plenty of small shops around and very close to Temple Bar where you have plenty of restaurants

If in Antiques shops you can find them 3 mins from apartment

The local area is a quiet leafy suburb of Dublin. Located just 5 minutes cycle from the city centre. There is a Dublin bike terminal at the end of the street and a card is available should you wish to cycle. Herbert park is close by as are a number of Georgian squares including Merrion Square, Fitzwilliam Square and St Stephens Green. Ranelagh is also very close which has a vibrant nightlife and restaurant scene.
Located in the "Silicon Valley" of Europe, this place is perfect for a professional on a short business trip, or a female traveller seeking safety and convenience.

The liberties is a historical area in central Dublin, transformed over the last 25 years from a largely working class area to a vibrant multicultural area with loads of different cuisine options literally on the doorstep. Our favourite restaurants are right on the street, including "Rottinculo" a lovely Italian just across the street and the hipster cafe "the Fumbally" about 200m up the road. Of course if you are in the mood for a take away from an typical Irish chipper the bistro across the street delivers in trumps.

Camden street with its many restaurants, pubs and clubs is just a 5 minute walk away and everything the city centre has to offer including high end shopping on Grafton street, just another 7 minute walk from there and of course Trinity College with the Book of Kells, one of the top 5 to see in the world according to the lonely planet.

Further up towards the Liffey is historical Christchurch Cathedral, a 10 minute walk from the apartment and the tren
Quiet, safe residential, close to Dublin Airport, leafy area, close to all amenities and friendly locals
Located in between city centre and the "Silicon Valley" of Europe, this place is perfect for a professional on a short business trip, or a female traveller seeking safety and convenience.
Centrally located, friendly quiet, family neighbourhood with good local cafes and amenities
The neighborhood is quiet and friendly, never had any problem, they are all nice Irish people.

Our period home is located in a quiet neighbourhood at the base of Killiney Hill. This is in the historic area of Killiney with it's many period houses. It is near to the splendid Killiney Bay with its beach that will suit hardy swimmers, but for the less intrepid it is still a wonderful place to go for a seaside stroll.
For more details see;
http://www.tripadvisor.ie/Attractions-g212297-Activities-Killiney_County_Dublin.html
The historic Heritage Town of Dalkey is nearby. With it's numerous restaurants and bars and added to it's literary past it is a place well worth a visit-from our home as it is just a short one stop hop away on the DART. For the more strenuous guests a lengthy walk to Dalkey could take in Killiney Hill and it's obelisk together with the spectacular 360deg panoramic views that this location provides -this includes views of: Killiney Bay from Dalkey to Bray Head( that has been rightly likened to Sorrento Bay in Italy), to Bray Head and the Sugarloa
Quiet mature residential area.
Two major supermarkets are on either side of the estate and local shops are also within a few minutes walk.

Located in Drumcondra Village, you will enjoy the peace and tranquility of village on the citys doorstep.

Drumcondra is blessed with an abundance of places to dine out and good bars

The house is right next to a very big park so if you like running/jogging/walking it is a real oasis and ideal for that.  It is also near the beach and the seaside areas of North Dublin.  The neighbourhood is a very old and established family area so very calm, friendly and secure.  All the necessary shops and facilities are close by.
Neighbourhood is very safe.  The house is situated beside the ward valley which is lovely for walking.

The neighborhood of Cabra/Phibsborough is relatively quiet and residential, with a real community feel. It's fantastic to be within walking distance of Dublin city centre but without the madness of staying right in the heart of it! The Phoenix Park, the Zoo, the National Botanic Gardens, historic Glasnevin Cemetry, the Mater Hospital and O'Connell Street are all close by, plus pubs, cafes and local shops with in wlking distance. If you enjoy rooting through charity/second hand shops, Phibsborough village is a must. Nearby Smithfield is fast becoming one of the coolest places in Dublin.

For fitness fans, there are so many options right on the doorstep, with lots of parks and the beautiful Royal Canal. A pay as you go gym/swimming pool is within walking distance too.

Experience the heart of Dublin.
Walking distance to everything, apartment is right beside Dublin's Iconic landmark, The Ha'Penny Bridge, Temple Bar is just across the river, 5 minutes to Trinity College.
Supermarket 2 minutes from the apartment.

GREAT location close the city centre in walking distance. Everything what you need is very close. Shopping, pubs, cafes, restaurants, gym, yoga, sightseeing.
Spar across the street, Tesco Express 2 mins walk

Dublin beach - 20 mins walk
Extremely save.

Smithfield is an old part of Dublin with a modern feel. The main square used to be a market square and there is still a horse fair there twice a year. You are right beside the Whiskey heritage centre, just a block from the river Liffey

Firhouse is a lovely, open, green residential area with shops, pubs and other amenities within walking distance. We are at the foot of the Dublin mountains and beside the M50 motorway. We personally love the The Hub Café and The Speaker Connolly pub for food. We are a short bus ride from other villages such as Terenure, Templeogue, Rathgar and Rathmines. We would also recommend the Hellfire Club walk which is suitable for families.
If you arrive in the early evening and want a bite to eat, the local pub (7 mins walk ), the Speaker Conolly, serves food before 8.15pm.
Ballsbridge is a vibrant upmarket area of Dublin.  Close to all the hustle and bustle of a big city.  Restaurants, shops and pubs are all easily accessible from our apartment.

Located in the Liberties in Dublin 8, experience both old and new Dublin. Dublin 8 is rapidly becoming known as one of 'the' trendy areas in Dublin but it is also shrouded in history and character. Start the day off with breakfast in the very trendy Fumbally cafe, take a stroll through St. Patrick's park or visit the Cathedral. Spend the afternoon investigating the hidden treasures in the antique shops on Francis St. whiskey tasting in Teelings Distillery,  or taking in the views of the city from the top of the Guinness storehouse and then finish the day in the local Fallons pub and meet some of the locals.

Skerries is a great neightbourhood with a lovely beach, good cafes (Olive is particularly nice ones) and a lovely harbour with restaurants and pubs. We think we live in one of the best spots as the house is in the heart of everything while at the same time being surrounded by green space. We are actually right beside the Mill Museum and the Skerries Tourist office.
2 minutes walk to Phoenix Park

Ideally situated within 20 min from the airport and city center. Shops, restaurants, coffee shops, pharmacy only 5-10 min away. Burrow beach 10 min.
Howth only 5 min by train or 30 min to walk.
Direct bus to Malahide village
Quiet, beautiful, tree-lined area right next to a famous Dublin park.
the old pedestrian quarter of Dublin city filled with history and culture.
Close to major tourist attractions such as: The Phoenix Park, Guiness Storehouse, Kilmainham Jail, Irish Museum of Modern Art and Dublin Zoo to name a few
Super cafes: swans, sea, harbour...
This is a very quiet neighborhood, and everybody who lives here respects this. As the location is in the immediate proximity of Dublin City Center, it makes it a very popular area for travelers.
Drumcondra is a very old gentrified neighbourhood, with lots of lovely Victorian street and coffee shops to be found in the nooks and crannies- explore- look at my guidebook

Stoneybatter is a gorgeous area, known more recently as a hipster-type neighbourhood in Dublin. It's 10 minutes walk to Europe's biggest city park - the Phoenix Park, but only 15 minutes walk into the very heart of the city. There are loads of cute cafes and what's known as Dublin's best gastropub all within minutes. It's a very safe and quiet area too.

Rooms are 3 minute walk from Luas

5 mins from the Kylemore road (McDonalds).
Local shops (Spar, post office, fast-food) close by.

Beautiful neighbourhood and only 25 mins walk to town centre. 10 mins walk to water and shops. Right on the bus line which will take you to swords (5mins) the airport (20 mins) and the city centre (25 mins). Malahide has a total of 41 eating establishments. So always something for everyone! Or you can order food to be delivered if you prefer to chill and relax in our home.

Once you are settled in, 20 minutes walk will bring you to the vibrant village of Malahide which boasts a lovely 12th century castle set on 250 acres of park land, there are over 25 restaurants to choose from in this award winning pretty seaside town along with traditional Irish pubs with live music. Ladies boutiques, a yachting marina and the beach are also a big feature in Malahide village.

A further five minutes along the coast is Portmarnock beach, nicknamed The Velvet Strand due to the beautiful smooth sand along the beach, and is popular with wind and kite surfers.

The local dou
There is a local pub, park, few take aways and restaurants, pharmacy, hair saloon, church and few shops within walking distance
Friendly family suburban neighbourhood
The house is in a quiet estate with green areas, close to shops and amenities.
Drimnagh is Dublin 12 approx. 5k from city centre and serviced by Bus and Luas.
Well established close to all amenities, bus route & Luas to City centre. 20 mins to Airport. Close to park. Walking distance to village & pub. Very friendly neighbourhood.
Great neighborhood, artistic community. Great  restaurants: Boqueria, Slice, Mulligans. Great local artisan deli Lilliput Stores

Adjacent to St Anne’s Park, The Red Stables (local market on Saturdays), Bull Island/Dollymount Strand and easy access to Dublin City centre.  Many pubs, restaurants and bars in Clontarf itself, especially Olive's Room, Bay, Fishbone, Kanoodle, Kinara, Yangs and many more in Vernon Avenue area.  Local Mace store and Tillies' Coffee Shop less than 5 minute walk.

The tower is 5 mins or less by car from Sutton , a beautiful village which has shops, restaurants, cafes .  Further on then is Howth Harbour you can take a trip out on a tour boat eat in one of the many many restaurants.  Take a stroll along the harbour and maybe a walk along the cliffs back  to the tower !.  Further on 15 - 20 mins is Dublin city centre.

Apartment complex sits on Smithfield Plaza. There's often something happening on the square itself, be it a market or film festival, sporting event up on a big screen, live performance of some kind etc. The Generator hostel next to the Jameson distillery keeps things lively. The Maldron hotel is there for a fancier stay if that's your thing. The bars, restaurants, nearby takeaways and cafes are generally very good. It's a great location, 15 minute walk away from the city centre. However, there are some very decent cafes and pubs and the Jameson Old Distillery / Visitor Centre is well worth a visit.

Recommended if you are looking for music, food or drinks: Third Space, My Meat Wagon, Oscars, Cinnamon, Dice Bar, The Cobblestones, Generator , Jameson Distillery, Fresh SuperMarket, Wuff, Frank Ryan's all surround the square and will welcome you in an authentic and genuine way.
Close to city center, 15 min walk. Grand Canal Dock is a 5 min walk.

This is a mature respectable neighbourhood and guests can look forward to having a comfortable and enjoyable stay.
Be sure to view our guidebook on our listings page which also has mapping feature of lots of Dublin's most revered attractions.

Rathgar is a quiet town in Dublin's Southside just 15 minutes away from the city centre by bus with a very regular service. If you like walking, St Stephen's Green or George's Street is a bit over half an hour away.

Rathgar has a great selection of local gourmet produce available in Super Valu and in The Butler's Pantry. The 108 Bar has an extensive local and international craft beer selection as well as a few rare whiskeys. The Bottlers Bank, just across the road, is more traditional, with original fittings and fantastic character.

Rathmines is a short walk down the road where there are bakeries, cafes, restaurants and a public swimming pool. The Blackbird was once considered a pub for an older generation, it now caters a younger crowd, with old beds being transformed into tables and an eclectic selection of board games. Mother Reilly's, known locally as Ma Reilly's, is a more traditional style, with most of its furniture and decor moved from an 18th century pub
In the heart of Dublin's docklands, we are surrounded by a range of restaurants and a short walk/tram ride to O'Connell Street.

In terms of a fully-rounded Dublin experience, the apartment couldn’t be more conveniently located. Whether it’s a walk down the wonderland of Grafton Street you’re after, or a perfect pint of Guinness in the Gravity Bar in the Guinness Store House; a tour through the cathedrals of St. Patrick and Christ Church, or a stroll down Dame Street to Trinity College, satisfaction is no more than ten minutes away.


The cobblestoned streets of Temple Bar, with its pubs, clubs, galleries, theatres and coffee shops, is also only ten minutes up the road. The new Teeling Whiskey Distillery is literally around the corner from the apartment, right beside the Dublin Food Co-op, a healthy food cooperative, housing an organic food shop, vegetable and market stalls, which run every week.

When I was growing up this stretch of the quays was full of book and antique shops, interspaced with solicitors offices (the Four Courts are just upstream). In the second half of the 20th. C, there were plans to demolish the historic buildings and widen the roads. It was left to decay, much as the opposite side of the river - Temple Bar, had done. Capel Street, around the corner is one of my favorite places in the city- still a mixture of tool shops, great value food and a bit of everything else thrown in. The fruit and veg. market is around the corner too- well worth a visit if you're interested in a bit of old Dublin.

Howth is a fishing and yachting port , and popular suburban resort on the north side of Howth Head 9 miles north east of the city centre. Its attractions are easily appreciated , particularly at the coast. Howth Head gives fine views of Dublin Bay an the Wicklow Mountains or Boyne Valley beyound . In the bay is the rocky bird sanctuary and monastic island of Irelands eye to which boat trips may be taken in the summer. Cliff paths lead around the coastline ,throught Howth village and its ruined abbey and past Baily Lighthouse. The15th century Howth Castle is inland parly ruinous . but with fine rhododendron gardens. A small but impressive , transport museum can be visited near the Dart railway station.

After the fashion of the Dublin Georgian squares, featuring a park in the centre: Crosthwaite Park was completed between 1860 and 1875.
Many of Dun Laoghaire’s most characteristic avenues run downhill at right angles to the sea, viewed in the distance.
The unique quality of 19th century Dun Laoghaire is the result of two products of the Steam Age , the steam ship and the railway ( Now the DART Trainline). A town begun in 1830, complete with every kind of public building, Banks, Post Office, Hospital, Schools, Convents and a Coastguard Station as well as those already described, was fully fledged by 1900.
Dun Laoghaire’s 19th century past paints a good picture of the Victorian way of life, and much of this is well reflected in the buildings of the town.

Donnycarney (Irish: Domhnach Cearnach, meaning Carney's Church) is a Northside suburb in the city of Dublin, Ireland. It is bordered by Beaumont, Artane, Killester and Marino, and lies in the postal districts of Dublin 3, 9 and 5. Donnycarney is a mostly residential area, located 5km from the centre of Dublin. It has a good range of amenities including restaurants, shops and a 3.25ha park, May Park (Donnycarney Park). The area is crossed by one of Dublin's "small rivers". Donnycarney is most notable as the home of Parnell Park, a Gaelic Athletic Association stadium where the Dublin inter-county teams play many of their matches, including lower-profile matches which do not warrant the use of Croke Park, the national stadium. Donnycarney is also home to well known GAA clubs Craobh Chiarain and St Vincents, who have their base where the area borders Marino, as well as Parnells GAA.
