A charming village with all you will need to enjoy you time here. . Just 3 miles / 4.8kms from the city centre,with frequent buses to the centre of Dublin almost on the doorstep. A great location to enjoy the village or from which to explore city and the surrounding countryside.
15 restaurants,4 supermarkets, 2 specialist butchers, 3 pubs, 5 hairdressers, 3 beauty salons, 2 pharmacies, local shops, bank and large local park, with children's play ground - you will want for nothing!
Lovely leafy area of Dublin 4  loads of bars restaurants; close to Herbert Park..  Churches coffee shops whatever you want...Most famous coffee kiosk top of the road..

The apartment is located in the centre of Dublin (D1). You are within minutes (walking) to all the main attractions such as: Trinity College, Guiness Storehouse, Grafton St., Temple Bar and concert venues.
We have around us many shops to buy groceries and shops from different countries with some exotic food.
Walking distance from very good restaurants as well.
Quiet suburban neighbourhood. Ideal base for Dublin visit and well located for national travel also.

We are lucky to live in one of the greenest areas of Dublin city. The gorgeous Phoenix Park, one of the largest enclosed urban parks in Europe, is our favorite oasis as you can walk or ride a bicycle for miles and it's just a few minutes walk away. The Irish National War Memorial Gardens is also right next to our apartment. You can go for a stroll down by the bank of the Liffey and watch the local rowing teams practice throughout the spring and summer. Up the road lies Kilmainham, home to the Kilmainham Gaol and the Royal Hospital.  The former is now a museum and the later houses the Irish Museum of Modern Art. Both are well worth visiting. The people in our building and neighborhood are quiet and friendly. The area is safe and clean.

The apartment is in the Liberties neighborhood of Dublin.

Guinness storehouse is less than 5 minutes away and a 10 minute walk will bring to the following attractions:

Jameson Distillery
IMMA
Christchurch cathedral
Dublinia Viking Musuem
St Patrick's Cathedral
Collins Barrack Musuem

The following can be reached in 15 minutes:

Temple Bar & Dame St
Phoenix Park
Kilmainham Goal
The Ha'penny Bridge


There is a great selection of cafes, bars and restaurants within easy reach of the apartment.

The property  is situated in the Grand Canal Dock area.  This is one of the most vibrant parts of the city.  Nicknamed 'Silicone Docks' the area is home to many of the leading global tech companies.  As the area has developed funky bars and restaurants to cater for all tastes have emerged giving you plenty of choice and variety.

The flat is located in one of the prime-most locations in Southern Dublin, i.e. Blackrock. The neighborhood is quiet and friendly with authentic Irish pubs in the vicinity. The Three Tun Tavern just around the corner serves Dublin’s cheapest liquor and has some great Irish food.

Great spot, so close to town. Just follow the road as it follows the Liffey River to Dublin, past the amazing Phoenix Park, then the Guiness Factory. You can't miss Dublin. Lovely new double-decker buses run all day and night, giving you a great view as you enjoy the 10-15 minute ride into town. A couple of lovely local pubs, pharmacy, newsagent and Spar supermarket/liquor store are just steps away. Parking is easy. Phoenix Park is a massive attraction in itself, with great walk and cycle tracks complimented by wild, but very tame deer (and ducks). A quiet village with a lot of life all around it!

Smithfield is a charming, up-and-coming neighbourhood in Dublin's city centre. It's full of cafes (hipster & non hipster), good ethnic food and friendly pubs. It contains the Jameson Distillery, the Cobblestone pub (home of great Irish Trad music), the Lighthouse Cinema & Cineworld. It's beside the Henry Street shopping district, which includes the Jervis Centre & Ilac Centre. It's two tram stops/ten minutes' walk away from the Abbey Theatre, O'Connell Street and The GPO.

Smithfield is a real mix of Old & New Dublin, where young couples, recent immigrants from all over the world, and families who have lived here for generations, all mingle.
Very good neighborhood, well connected with all kinds of transport.

The great thing about staying in Dalkey is the closeness to the sea, the variety of coastal walks with views of Dubin/Killiney Bay, access to beach and yet less than 10mins walk there is a commuter train to Dublin City Centre which takes approximately 25minutes. During the day it is lovely to enjoy a coffee or lunch in one our favourite places, The Tramyard or Cornernote cafes. In the evening our favourite restaurants are 1909, Ouzos, DeVilles or Kathmandu………… out of the 11 available!! And if you want to dine more casually at night we would recommend the steak on the stone in the Queens pub (est. 1745) or Charcuterie/Cheese boards in The Grapevine our local wine bar which is also a gallery.
For those of you interested in history you must not miss a visit to Dalkey Castle Heritage Centre where professional actors bring history to life with a fun theatre performance as part of the guided tour. You can also buy a ticket here to take a small boat to Dalkey Island at Coliemore Harb

Dublin 7 is a great part of Dublin and I really enjoy living here.  I regularly go running and walking in the Phoenix Park which is within a stones throw from my front door.  Stoneybatter, the lovely neighbourhood behind my housing estate has a number of new cafés with excellent barista coffee, for those who enjoy it! Some of my favourites are Slice, Love Supreme or Proper Order Coffee in Smithfield.  Likewise there are numerous modern eateries in the area, all the way in towards O' Connell street.  Tourist attractions abound: The Phoenix Park, The Guinness Storehouse, IMMA, The Royal Hospital and Kilmainham Gaol are all nearby within walking distance.  Otherwise the RHA, The National Gallery of Ireland, Hugh Lane Gallery are other excellent galleries for art lovers.  Shopping is endless, as are options for music, theatre and restaurants!

Raheny village is a nice litlle village that offer a wide range of shop and restaurant. The village is lively and very friendly. The major feature is the nearly 5 km beach known as Dollymount Strand, on the nature reserve of North Bull Island. There are also two parks: North Bull Island itself and Saint Anne's Park (formerly the home of the Guinness family of brewing and later banking fame), as well as Edenmore Park (with a pitch and putt course and playing fields)
There is excellent walking and cycling on the sea front (one can walk or bike from Howth to Dun Laoghaire, on North Bull Island, in St. Anne's Park and around the leafy streets.
Herbstreet and HQ are two of the best places for a lovely brunch or great dinner and only 2 minutes away.

We live in a great part of the city, a quiet, very pretty Victorian street with the city centre on its doorstep. The Neighbourhood, Broadstone is a collection of streets of Victorian redbrick cottages surrounding a gorgeous little Park. It's a perfect example of an oasis - calm and quiet but just minutes from the City centre and all of its amenities. James Joyce lived two doors away where he wrote those nasty letters which were discovered under the floorboards!

Our neighbourhood is located right in the Business & Financial District of the city. During the day it's busy and bustling, but thankfully at night it is peaceful and beautiful, with plenty of modern street lighting and architecture to explore. There's a Spar (convenience store) located just downstairs, as well as a Subway, Coffee Shop and Burrito Bar. There's also plenty of restaurants and bars around. The area is quite safe and only 100m from the river Liffey where you can walk out to the docklands or back towards Temple Bar.

You really are in the centre of everything in this apartment and you can walk to everything with ease, although the Luas is just around the corner on abbey street and there are numerous bus routes on the quays. There is a starbucks below the apartment and Temple bar is just over the Halpenny bridge so close you will be able to stroll home from the bar

The house is a 15 minute walk from Blackrock and Monkstown villages both with great restaurants, pubs and shops. The seafront at Seapoint is a 10 min jog (or 20 min walk) away and is great for a swim. We are a 10 minute drive from Dun Loaghaire harbour where we enjoy going for walks on the pier.
Dublin city centre is just 25 mins away by car, bus and train.

House is located in the middle of Rathcoole in a quiet cul de sac. Its a lovely family neighbourhood and is a very quiet area.
Yet it is just 2 minutes walking distance to public transport and all the shops on the main street.
There are a number of restaurants, take aways and pubs where guest can have a meal and socialise. Also various shops for all your needs. Large Shopping centre is within 10 min drive from the area. There is also famous Avoca centre which is known for its health quality products and healthy food. They now have a yoga centre in it too.
Large Rathcoole park is just opposite Avoca which is in 5- 7 min walk from the house.
Another 10-15min walk and you are in the middle of City West and Saggart area where City West hotel and business centre are located.

Guest car parking is available.
Central and boasting all necessary services like shops, restaurants, pubs etc.

Best location in Dublin next to city's famous Long Stone Beer Garden (opposite side to apt which faces Tara st so no noise whatsoever from bars) with restaurants, nightlife, city sights, transport links outside the door of this warm modern apt. Time on foot from front door to the following:

Temple Bar: 2 minutes
Trinity: 2 minutes
River Liffey: 2 minutes
Dart and train: Tara st station 2 mins
O'Connell st: 4 minutes
Grafton St: 4 minutes
IFSC/Financial Centre: 6 mins
Busarus Main Bus Station: 6 mins
Chaplains Comedy Club & Bar: 1 min
Mulligans famous stout bar: 1 min
Vintage Kitchen Restaurant: 1 min
Pubs / restaurants/ Grocery store/ coffee shops: Less than 1 minute

East Wall is an interesting part of Dublin: lots of houses which are over 100 years old mixed with new apartments. The area is (URL HIDDEN) one of the few places you'll see in Dublin where kids still play out on the street by themselves. But you'll see it's modernising and up-and-coming: we just got a Starbucks and a McDonalds...the Central Bank of Ireland moved in recently, and (SENSITIVE CONTENTS HIDDEN) is opening an office here!
Lovely neighbourhood full of pubs, cafes and a shopping centre 2 minutes walk away
It's the best location in Dublin

Just North of the River Liffey and a short walk from historic O'Connell Street, this is the very heart of the city centre and the perfect location for anyone wishing to explore the city by foot.

One of Dublin’s main shopping hubs is O'Connell Street (and its tributary, the ever-busy Henry Street), which culminates in a spearhead of excellent museums dotted around Parnell Square (most notably the Hugh Lane Gallery). To the west of here is the up-and-coming Smithfield and, further still, the vast Phoenix Park (also home to Dublin Zoo) while just across the bridge to the south is the formidable campus of Trinity College, with its ancient claim to fame in pride of place in the Old Library & Book of Kells.

You have everything at your doorstep in the city centre and there's an exciting mix of cultures and ideas to cater for every whim you might have.

Please take a look at the guidebook on my listing for recommended places to eat and drink in the area!

Harold's Cross is a wonderful historic, residential area, with lots of parks, fine restaurants and fun bars. There now are 2 Michelin Bib Gourmand in close proximity to the house (Craft and Bastible (do make reservations well in advance of your visit!)). Plus the city center is only 5 min bus/taxi ride away or if you're up for it the centre is only a 30 min walk away.

The house is in a very quiet, residential area, with very little traffic. It is situated on the corner of a very picturesque small square.

There is a supermarket and a range of small shops 5 minutes walk away.
This street is truly unique with great pride taken by the residents to maintain this iconic Dublin street.

5 mins walk from one of the biggest parks in Europe The Phoenix Park. Dublin Zoo, stunning wild deer, beautiful walks and many cafe and delicious restaurants within the park.
10 minute walk to very large supermarket and 10 minutes to
Gastro pub The Hole in the Wall.
25 mins walk to the historical Smithfield Square which hosts the Jameson Whiskey Distillery and the famous Cobblestone Pub.
45 mins walk to city centre. 15 mins walk to Heuston train station.
Apartment set in a beautiful estate surrounded by a park.  Coffee shop, Supermarket, Chemist, etc all available locally

As returned Irish expats (we have lived in the U.S., Canada, Central Europe, the Middle East and Spain) we now love living in Sandymount, often described as "a village within Dublin City", a comfortable coastal enclave.
Sandymount Strand is described as "the most famous beach in Irish fiction" based on references in the James Joyce classic "Ulysses". Sandymount is prized by its residents for its classic Village Green, a focal point for local community activity, surrounded by restaurants and other retail services.

We also treasure the ready access to the sea and the city, to top class universities (e.g. Trinity and U.C.D), cultural and sporting facilities (Royal Dublin Society, Aviva Stadium, Grand Canal Theatre), excellent restaurants and shopping. We walk a lot, often to the facilities mentioned above, but also into the wilder nature trails just south of us in the Dublin and Wicklow mountains.
A very quite and friendly neighborhood. Lots of kids play out on the green and its a very safe area.
Trinity college, grand canal is theatre, metro on square, national art gallery, natural history museum, government buildings,

Our neighborhood is a residential area, very quiet and very safe. It is a short walk from local shops and a well stocked supermarket. A 5 min walk will bring you to our local park, which has a children's playground, tennis courts, and a spectacular view over the city and Dublin bay.

This is a beautiful part of Dublin with leafy streets containing elegant Georgian and Victorian family homes. Donnybrook is a thriving village with fantastic restaurants, lively pubs and wine bars and shops. The city centre is a 15 minute walk away, along one of the most elegant Georgian streetscapes in the world and through the beautiful St. Stephen's Green park.
Convenience to city centre, Phoenix park and M50
Best restaursnts in Dublin just around the corner, in Ranelagh Village.

A relatively new neighbourhood in Dublin that is very close to the Gibson Hotel and the 3Arena. It is easily accessible on foot to the IFSC (Financial Services Centre) and the National Convention Centre. Other venues can be reached by a short 10-15 minute cab ride, such as the Aviva stadium, Bord Gais (Libeskind) Theatre and Grand Canal Dock, city centre (including Temple Bar), Trinity College, East Wall Business Park. Airport is about 20 minutes away via Dublin Port Tunnel.

Cafes:
The Gibson hotel is a great spot for coffee or drink if you want somewhere classy. There is also a Starbucks nearby, too. If you get the Luas tram to the Jervis stop, there is an 'Italian quarter' there with a nice selection of authentic Italian restaurants and cafe. There are also several good cafes in Mayor Square in the IFSC. My own favourite cafes in the city include Queen of Tarts in Temple bar and Dame Street (URL HIDDEN) and Busyfeet and Clement & Pekoe (URL HIDDEN) both on South Willi

Rathgar is a small peaceful village that is only a short drive or bus journey to Dublin City Centre.

It is the perfect location for a traveller who wants to enjoy all of the excitement of the city while retreating to a quiet neighbourhood to get some rest!

In the neighbourhood, we have parks, St Luke's Hosptial, Emerald Cultural Institute, Trinity College Halls of residence and much more!

A ten minute walk will bring you to Palmerston Park, a lovely park to relax and stroll around.

St Luke's Radiation Oncology Hospital is a five minute walk.

For students attending Emerald's professional English course, my place is perfectly located - just a 12 minute walk.

It is also only a 3 minute drive from the Trinity College Halls of Residence that are located on Dartry Road - perfect for any visiting parents!
Smithfield is one of the most attractive area in Dublin, close to everything in town, quite and peaceful during the night time
The area is one of the best are to live in. Within minutes walking to many amenities in city centre. There are 24h shops two minutes walking. Located in a safe closed house complex.

There are lots of embassies around this area. It's so quiet and beside beautiful canal. Easy access to get transportation, the bus stop is 2 min walk, Luas (tram) station is 5 min walk.
The convinience store is 2 min walk, supermarkets are 10 min walk. There are nice cafe and one of the nicest Guinness pub around this area.
Smithfield is a safe area, walking distance to many of Dublin tourists spots.
Smithfield is a safe area, within walking distance to many of Dublin tourists spots.

House is located in the middle of Rathcoole in a quiet cul de sac. Its a lovely family neighbourhood and is a very quiet area.
Yet it is just 2 minutes walking distance to public transport and all the shops on the main street.
There are number of restaurants, take aways and pubs where guest can have a meal and socialise located on the main street. Also various shops for all your needs. Large Shopping centre is within 10 min drive from the area. There is also famous Avoca centre which is known for its cafes and healthy organic food and range of houseware products. They now have a yoga centre in it too.
Large Rathcoole park is just opposite Avoca which is in 5- 7 min walk from the house.
Another 10-15min walk and you are in the middle of City West and Saggart area where City West hotel and business centre are located.

Our area is quiet but very centrally located, and we think it is Dublin's best suburb by far! Enjoy a seaside stroll along Sandymount Strand or follow the path through the Irishtown Nature Reserve to really blow out the cobwebs with a walk along the Great South Wall, out to the landmark red Poolbeg Lighthouse.

Away from the beach, our house is close to some of the buzziest bars and best restaurants in Dublin including Slattery's, the Vintage Inn, the Bath, Junior's, Paulie's, The Old Spot, the Chophouse, and Farmer Brown's in the trendy Beggar’s Bush area. We are just between the village green of Sandymount, with its small boutiques, book shop, cafes and restaurants, and Ringsend, with additional options for coffee, pubs and cuisine. Both villages have takeaway food options or can meet your grocery needs (large Tesco in Sandymount, Tesco Express Ringsend, family butcher shops in both villages. Sandymount also has a health food shop and the artisan Butler's Pantry)
About a 10-15min walk to St. Stephens Green (most central park in Dublin) as well as close to grafton street (for shopping). Temple bar is around 20-25min walk.

Monkstown is a beautiful seaside village with Seapoint swimming area  just five minutes from the house. Monkstown village is known for its unique selection of excellent restraunts and botiques such as Avoca, Lobstar, Thats Amore and many more. The village is just 10 minutes walk from the house. Blackrock village is 20 mins walk away and Dunlaoghaire is 30 mins walk. The number 7 bus passes along monkstown road and will bring you to the city centre in 35 mins. Also the Dart station is 5 mins walk away and will also bring you to the city centre in 20 mins.
Close to beautiful coastline and charming coastal towns and villages. Easy access to the city centre.

Chapelizod is a beautiful neighbourhood steeped in history and from some aspects it looks like it hasn't changed in 200 years. The views of nature and the river are some of the best in Dublin. You get that priceless feeling here of being in the countryside and the city at the same time. It is a convenient journey by bus into the city centre and only a 15 euro taxi fare home in the evening after a night out. There are some lovely little pubs and restaurants in the village if you prefer to stay local and lets not forget about the access to The Phoenix Park which is just 5 min walk from the front door! The park is absolutely spectacular with its own herd of wild deer and a multitude of walks and or drives around 707 hectares of green fields and forests. A must see when in Dublin.

The neighborhood is a mature suburb of Dublin (Dublin 5) close to Dublin City Centre. It is a quite neighborhood. Artane/Beaumount has 2 grocery shops (Tesco/Lidle) as well as a number of bars, cafes and restaurants.
Leafy suburb with parks galore and super shopping in the biggest shopping centre in Ireland Dundrum Shopping Centre. 5 mins walk
Clontarf is close to the coast for walk or run , cafes & coffees close to city and Harry Byrnes pub walking distance

Temple Bar is a unique place
Old building but nice and clean apartment
This is an old building the main door entrance can be tricky for some traveller be aware of it so do not expect to find new door system
Private dormer bungalow up a lane
Nice areas around the neighbourhood, supermarket, coffee shops, gym
Suburban quiet estate with all amenities close by

Ranelagh centre is a 15 minute walk, which has a bunch of nice pubs and restaurants. There are a few grocery stores, pharmacies, ATM, bakery, restaurants, pubs, and takeaway about a 5-10 minute walk to the centre of Donnybrook.

Sandymount is a quiet,select and safe neighbourhood within 30 mins walk to college greene (Trinity College) in the city. It is well served by bus and rail. All the local amenities you could want are available locally. Tennis club, cricket club, gym and sports club. Restaurants and local bars within 5 mins walk. And the Tesco supermarket is open 14 hrs everyday and do deliveries via tel or online orders.

Smithfield is a trendy inner city area just north of the river Liffey. Some local Artisian highlights of the Smithfield complex include the Light House Cinema/Gallery, the Generator Hostel, Third Space Cafe, Oscars Bar & Restaurant and the Fresh Good Food Shop.

Despite the excellent location, the area is very quiet and removed from the bustling nightlife districts of Dublin city centre. Furthermore, the area is very safe and the building is secure.
Peaceful neighbourhood in a street that becomes Dublin favourite place on sunny days.

Our neighborhood is one of the best in the city for inviting cozy cafes,  excellent restaurants, nightlife  and its great ethnic and social diversity.  Plus all the best cultural and tourist sites are within walking distance, with St. Patrick's cathedral and Stephen's Green just a few blocks away.  Then you can discover some hidden gems, like the Iveagh Gardens, old Jewish neighborhood, and Grand Canal full of swans with a 5 minute radius.
Gainsborough is a family neighborhood with open space green areas nearby. Close to local shops and church.

Within minutes of the house are three supermarkets and a wonderful grocery/deli where in-store chefs make meals of the highest quality. There is also a shopping centre within 5 minutes walk with a café, pizzeria, hairdresser and chemist and just a couple of minutes further on is the local pub, McCormack’s, which serves excellent food all day.

The 46A bus stops 70 metres from the house, this route will have you in the city in 30/40 minutes. There is also the option to take the train from Dún Laoghaire to the city or in the opposite direction along the coastline towards Wicklow and further afield. There are lots of choices.

You don't need a car to enjoy the multitude of amenities in Dún Laoghaire and the surrounding areas. The coastline is 1.9km from the house: it’s a 5 minute bus ride or 20/25 minute walk depending on your level of fitness. Enjoy long walks on the East & West Piers in Dún Laoghaire and the coastline. Literary lovers will enjoy the Joyce Tower in S
Enniskerry and the Powerscourt Estate are 10 minutes by car or bus and the Dundrum Town Centre with mall, restaurants and entertainment is 12 minutes by car or bus.

The area of Camden street is a hip, lively and vibrant place. Great for local bars and cheap eats. A great place for anyone looking to see where real Dubliners go out!

Close to Dublin's historical centre. Walking distance to everywhere in the city centre.
Beautiful upmarket and safe area, very close to everything!

Our home is a perfect base for visiting many of Dublin’s attractions. We are closer to some of the attractions than if you were coming from the city centre. The Guinness Brewery, the Teelings Brewery, the Irish Museum of Modern Art and Phoenix Park are all within quick reach on public transport.
Drimnagh is a very quiet, safe and old south-west Dublin suburb situated along the canal. Our street is full of elderly residents and families with young children. The actors Gabriel Byrne and Patrick Bergin grew up here, while Phil Lynott comes from Crumlin around the corner.

There is a strip of shops with butchers, newsagents, off license and vegetable shop just a short walk from the house. And the area is well-served with three excellent supermarkets. There is a Supervalu (mix of normal and high-end food), Aldi and Lidl, all within a five-minute drive/15 minute walk away.

Overlooking the Guinness Brewery and river Liffey, beside the Phoenix Park, near Dublin Zoo, adjacent to Heuston Station, a stone’s throw from the Collins Barracks Museum, on the Luas (tram) line, neighboring Stoneybatter which is known as one of Dublin's hippest areas, with plenty of dining and drinking options. Laid-back cafes serve artisanal coffee, while sleek restaurants feature creative global cuisine and modern takes on traditional food. Nightlife can mean lively folk music at a pub or casual drinks at a craft-beer bar. The Jameson Distillery Bow Street offers tours and tastings for those interested in Irish whiskey.
Tipperary House is the perfect starting point for whatever brings you to Dublin.

The neighbourhood is made up of a mix of locals and students and as a result there are great local amenities to service both, with great local cafes, parks and bars within strolling distance -Walking distance to Stephens Green area of town is about 15/20 minutes through the trendy Camden Street area with fantastic pubs, restaurants and shops en route

Overlooking the Guinness Brewery and river Liffey, beside the Phoenix Park, near Dublin Zoo, adjacent to Heuston Station, a stone’s throw from the Collins Barracks Museum, on the Luas (tram) line, neighboring Stoneybatter which is known as one of Dublin's hippest areas, with plenty of dining and drinking options. Laid-back cafes serve artisanal coffee, while sleek restaurants feature creative global cuisine and modern takes on traditional food. Nightlife can mean lively folk music at a pub or casual drinks at a craft-beer bar. The Jameson Distillery Bow Street offers tours and tastings for those interested in Irish whiskey.
Tipperary House is the perfect starting point for whatever brings you to Dublin.

We are right in the middle of city centre. You can basically do the vast majority of sightseeing by foot and  all buses and the train station are at our doorstep should you need to take a bus or the train somewhere. Conolly station (train station) and Busaras (bus station) are just around the corner from us.
15 minutes walking to O'Connell Street, 10 minutes walking to Templer Bar and downtown. 1 minute walking to the subway, taxis on the corner of the apartment.

There are some nice local restaurants within 5 minutes from our home. These include "Kinara" Pakistani restaurant, "Kanoodle" Thai Take away,  'Moloughneys" All day family friendly restaurant with great food, "Bay" Restaurant and 'Yangs' Chinese Restaurant which is just down the road.

I love Dun Laoghaire for many reasons. The main one is because the house is a 5 minute walk from the sea with most beautiful pier walk and panoramic views of Dublin Bay. Other things I like are:
The city centre is just 20 mins by train (Dart).
The farmers market every Sunday in People's Park with food stalls from all around the world.
The Forty Foot bathing area in Sandycove.
Teddy's ice cream parlour beside People's Park. Yummy!!
12 screen cinema.
Theatre.
Beautiful new library.
Coffee shops (eg Starbucks)
Cafes (eg Harry's Cafe, Itsabagel)
Restaurants (Hartleys, Olivettos, and close by Salt and FXBs in Monkstown)
Supermarkets Tesco and Supervalu.
Close by Killiney hill for breathtakingly beautiful walks in nature and views of Dublin Bay.
County Wicklow the garden of Ireland is on the door step.
My favourite food shop in Dublin, Cavistons, is just 8 mins down the road in Glasthule fabulous fish, vegetables, cheese

Within 20mins bus to city centre, bus stops right outside the door.

We are two minute walk from small supermarket and a 10 minute walk from Charlestown Shopping Centre and Cinema, Lidl and Aldi.

Temple Bar is a Vibrant area full of life, museums, and my favourite Irish Art-Cinema the Irish Film Institute. You may enjoy exploring all is many modern and old buildings and perhaps meeting some of it's Pleasant, eccentric, regular dwellers. I really love it here, as it is Eclectic and full of charm.

Dundrum Town Centre (shopping, restaurants, entertainment)
Dundrum village - pubs, restaurants, shops etc
LUAS yram line - quick hop to city centre.
Parks:

Airfield Estate,

Major Supermarkets

Leopardstown Race Course

Ormonde Quay is the most central location in Dublin, it allows traditional Dublin to mix  and blend with all that any modern city has to offer. Dublin is a multicultural treasure trove with bustling restaurants, bars and cultural districts and ormonde quay is at the centre
A fantastic area close to all of Dublin's famous and historic attractions. There are pubs on every corner, restaurants everywhere and the pedestrian only shopping district is only moments away.

The neighborhood is very quiet and safe.   There are shops and local pubs (with restaurants) within walking distance.  Waterstown Park and The Phoenix Park are close by for those who like the outdoors. Located close to the M50 and on a quality bus corridor to the city centre with buses passing every 5 minutes.  Liffey Valley Shopping Centre is walking distance or one bus stop away, it has a huge selection of shops, restaurants and cinemas.

The House is situated in a very quiet laneway, right in the heart of Ranelagh, which is a very vibrant area full of restaurants, bars and quirky shops.
A Lidl supermarket is 2 mins walk and has everything you need at low prices, a larger supermarket is appx 3 mins walk as is a Spar . There is also a bakery, a number of delis, pizzerias and loads of coffeee shops.
We have a 8th century Round Tower. At present the County Council is building an Interpretive Centre and renovating old house for use as Cafe and Museum.

Bray is a fun place to spend a week end and good place to base yourself to visit the attractions in Wicklow or in Dublin. Visit the Harbour bar voted the best pub in the world by the lonely planet guide. Good selection of restaurants and activities on the beach such as walking hiking cycling canoeing .

The owner-occupied development is adjacent to the beautiful Palmerston Park (less than 50 metres from the front door).

A wide variety of boutique shops, including a butcher, green grocer, fish monger, off license, pharmacy and Tesco Express are just a 10-12 min walk away on Rathmines Road Upper. Rathmines centre is about a 20 min walk away.

The Dartry neighbourhood is one of Dublin's most beautiful, with wide, leafy streets, large gardens and public parks. Local shops all stock excellent local produce and add to the relaxed vibe of the neighbourhood. The famous Dropping Well pub/restaurant is less than a 10 min walk away. Both Rathmines and Ranelagh are within easy walking distance and both have many excellent pubs and restaurants (even faster on bike!).

CAFE:
Il Valentino: an Italian Artisan Bakery and Cafe. Great variety of sweet and sour pastries, cakes and sandwiches.Opening times: Mon-Fri 7am-7pm, Sat-Sun: 9am-6pm.


Bb's: coffee shop with pastries, sandwiches and brunch options; a great place to seat outside if the weather is nice. Good coffee too. Opening times: Mon-Fri 8am-4pm, Sat-Sun: 10am-4pm.

Lolly and Cooks: coffee Shop is at the same building with good selections of muffins, gluten free options and brunch. Opening times: Mon-Fri 7:30am-6pm, Sat-Sun: 8:30am-6pm.

Starbucks has just opened 1 minute away on the 2 Cardiff Ln. Opening times: Mon-Fri 7am-9pm, Sat-Sun: 9am-8pm.

Just North of the River Liffey and a short walk from historic O'Connell Street, this is the very heart of the city centre and the perfect location for anyone wishing to explore the city by foot.

One of Dublin’s main shopping hubs is O'Connell Street (and its tributary, the ever-busy Henry Street), which culminates in a spearhead of excellent museums dotted around Parnell Square (most notably the Hugh Lane Gallery). To the west of here is the up-and-coming Smithfield and, further still, the vast Phoenix Park (also home to Dublin Zoo) while just across the bridge to the south is the formidable campus of Trinity College, with its ancient claim to fame in pride of place in the Old Library & Book of Kells.

You have everything at your doorstep in the city centre and there's an exciting mix of cultures and ideas to cater for every whim you might have.

Please take a look at the guidebook on my listing for recommended places to eat and drink in the area!

The actual complex itself is very quiet and it is in walking distance to a lovely supermarket and two coffee shops. Dundrum is a nice residential area south of the city, the Town Centre (www.dundrum.ie)  has tons of shopping, restaurants and bars as well as a 12 screen cinema, theatre and children's soft play centre. We are within easy reach of the Dublin/Wicklow mountains and great connections to the city centre, airport and rest of the country. It is also perfectly located to allow you to explore Dublin city centre and its surrounding countryside.

Dundrum is a very long established area of Dublin, with records and excavations going back to the 6th Century. The Normans built a castle there in the 13th Century.
Dundrum has embraced the needs of modern living with impressive innovation and scale. The superb Dundrum Town Centre was opened in 2005 and has expanded and improved further since then. Dundrum Town Centre contains a myriad of world renowned brands and a rich array of Irish & international retail outlets, restaurants and other leisure facilities.
The retail brands in the Town Centre include French Connection, Gant, Gap, Harvey Nichols, Hollister, House of Fraser, Life Style Sports, Louis Copeland, Bershka, Best, Boss, Elverys, Dune, Diesel, Massimo Dutti, McGurks Golf, Next, Penneys, Pull & Bear, Snow Rock, Sunglass Hut, Superdry, Timberland, T.K Maxx, Tommy Hilfiger, Weir & Sons, Zara.
The restaurants and cafes in the Centre include Roly Saul, Rock Lobster at Harvey Nicholls, TGI Fridays, Siam, The Counter,

This mews building is set in the heart of Georgian Dublin. There are two apartments in this building. Chez Jay 1 has 3 bedrooms and is located upstairs. Chez Jay 2 has 2 bedrooms and is located on the ground floor. It was built in 1792 and was originally the stables of one of the great houses in Fitzwilliam Square. It is within short walking distance of great restaurants, pubs, the Shelbourne and the Merrion Hotels and Grafton Street. It is very close to the National Art Gallery and Government buildings. Ireland’s finest Michelin star restaurants are all within easy walking distance. While the area is quiet, there is a real sense of being in the centre of everything. There are lovely walks along the canal and in the parks of Merrion Square and St Stephens Green.

The Camden Street/Portobello area is one of the very best in Dublin – lively, multicultural, full of pubs, coffee shops, restaurants, music venues and night clubs. Whelans, Dublin's most important music venue is around the corner on Wexford Street. Pub-of-the-year winners Devitt's is even closer and also has live music every night.

Other places of interest in the immediate vicinity include: St Patrick's Cathedral, Marsh's Library, The Irish-Jewish Museum, the birthplace of George Bernard Shaw, the National Concert Hall, the Iveagh Gardens, St Stephen's Green … and many more.

Grafton Street, Trinity College, the Parliamentary buildings, the National History Museum and the National Gallery are within a radius of 10-15 mins walk. So too are Dublin Castle and the wonderful Chester Beattie Library.

The thriving nightlife of George's Street, South William Street and Dame Lane – and the more tourist-focused Temple Bar are within 15mins walk.

Croke Park, home of the GAA and Ireland's Gaelic Games with an 800 000 seating capacity, is just around the corner.

CAFES AND RESTAURANTS

There are several cafes and restaurants nearby that I really like. n Drumcondra there's Nelly's, an art cafe type of place in a community arts centre. They do really nice breakfasts and lunches, and lovely coffee and cakes.

Independent Pizza - great pizzas and good value. Similarly Wallace's Asti. Lovely Food Co. serve breakfast, lunch and dinner; a tiny space and tasty food.
Anderson's Cafe and Creperie, also from breakfast to dinner.
Le Petit Breton, very friendly staff and nice crepes.

In Fairview:
Kennedy's Food Store and Cafe
Bram's Cafe,
Chopped Sal
The Appartment is in the middle of the Grand Canal Docks close to the quay and to the city center (15 mins walk).

Terenure Village is a 5 minute walk. You are spoiled for choice when it comes to good pubs and restaurants. Try Vaughan's pub at the crossroads for great food and Brady's pub for weekend traditional music. Then there is the Italian, the Japanese, the Indian.... Better still, Mayfield restaurant is only 2 minutes from our front door.

Our neighborhood is very quiet, which is unusual for the city centre location. So we have all of the life of the big city on our doorstep, but without the noise-perfect! It's also just 15 minutes drive from the airport-very convenient.
Alensgrove can be found within an enclosed courtyard on the outskirts of the lively Leixlip Village. Shops and Transport services can be found within walking distance.
My house is located in a small quiet cul de sac.

The neighborhood is ideally located with dart station, major bus routes, St. Ann's Park and Dollymount Strand all within walking distance. Clontarf village, Raheny village and Killester village, all a ten minute walk. City centre is ten minute on the dart and Croke park and the airport both a 15 minute drive.
Very peaceful neighbourhood, house is situated in a cul de sac with a large green area in front of house for the local kids to play in

Our neighbourhood is very quiet and safe even tough you have all the shops, take-aways, bank and cafés just behind the house.
If you like walking and want to enjoy and know the neighbourhood OConnell Street is only 20min away!

Location and quiet. We walk everywhere - into the city, the local pubs & restaurants, the supermarket, the beach, the park. The area is quiet and our house is South facing so plenty of evening light & sun

Our house is on a quiet residential road right next to Phoenix Park. There is a huge supermarket 10 minutes walk away, along with lots of smaller shops including pharmacies, cafes, takeaways, etc.
The famous Hole in the Wall bar is only a short stroll away with more great restaurants and bars close by in Stoneybatter.
It is a lovely quiet family oriented residential area in a very established part of Dublin.

Ranelagh is a bustling, vibrant Dublin village, full of great pubs, coffee shops and restaurants. 20 minute’s walk away, you are in St Stephen’s Green and Grafton Street, the very heart of Dublin. You are also a 10 minute drive from the RDS, home to the Dublin Horse Show and many conferences and events, and our famous Aviva stadium that hosts sports teams from all over the world to play our national sporting heroes.
The IFSC, The Convention Centre, city centre, Grand Canal Dock, train station and LUAS (tram) services are all within walking distance.

At the top of Stoneybatter the house is an enjoyable paced 30 minute walk to Temple Bar. While Stoneybatter & Smithfield has the delicious Mulligans Bar with locally sourced menu or WUFF or for a 5 star morning coffee & sausage roll there's Love Supreme❤️
For some authentic traditional music & a top pint of Guinness only 10 minutes away there's the renowned Cobblestone Pub on Smithfield Square with a cheeky tasting/tour of Jameson's across & the excellent live experience of The Story of the Irish. The list goes on for art lovers & explorers of interesting spots where memories are made & with the ever the classic walk/cycle/outdoor yoga in Phoenix Park surrounded by deer to name the animal free to roam unlike the Elephants at the zoo! The house is also 15 minutes by taxi from the airport & easy for access to Heuston Station for seeing all of fair Ireland as well linked to all of Dublin
Historic maritime town overlooking Dublin Bay!

Dublin 4 is a leafy and affluent part of Dublin.  Property prices are the highest here in the country.  There's no end of famous bars and great restaurants nearby.  My favourite is the tasting menu at Forest Avenue just down the road.  O'Brien's pub is one of the best in Ireland (and it's even closer) and O'Donoghues is your best bet for authentic irish music 7 nights of the week.  There's a whole range of parks, the famous canal and plenty of local grocers and butchers.  It's a lovely part of the world. If you're a foodie there's one of the best shops in the country for all your obscure ingredients (about 10mins walk away).

The Temple Bar district is a lively area of Dublin! There is plenty of pubs with live music sessions, excellent restaurants and coffee bars. Every Saturday there is a food market and the artisan craft art market within 5 min walking from the apartment.
From this location you can reach all major attraction simply walking.
My home is located right near the sea front of Dublin Bay offering a 12 mile walk with fantastic views.

Castleforbes is a relatively new and well-maintained residential apartment complex situated just North of the River Liffey in the heart of the former Docklands.
The area is home to the main concert venue in the City - the 3Arena, the Convention Centre and the IFSC- Financial District: All are within 3-10 mins stroll from the apartment.
The neighbourhood has an abundance of bars, cafes and restaurants (Gibson Hotel, Spencer Hotel, CHQ building, ELY restaurant, Starbucks, Costa Coffee etc.) and is also a short stroll (10-15 mins) from the Grand Canal Dock area on the other side of the river - accessed via the Samuel Beckett (Calatrava-designed) bridge.
The City Centre is a mere 10 mins journey by LUAS tram and can also be reached by walking for 20/25 mins along the Riverside promenade.
In short, it's all about Location, Location, Location!
Quiet, safe and residential area very close to city centre + Rathmines, Ranelagh and Rathgar villages. Close to shops, Irish pubs, restaurants and beautiful Palmerston Park.

Mature neighbourhood very quiet and so convenient to swords main street. Shopping Centre Restaurants Bars Literally 5 mins walk from my home .
Parking is available in driveway
Airport 8 mins drive from house

Portobello is as close a city-suburb as you can get, a stone's throw from the action. It's a decidedly trendy and cosmopolitan neighbourhood with a plethora of great and interesting bars and restaurants to choose from. This is a great neighbourhood to walk to with ease from the city centre.

Mount Brown is a very historically rich area. We're located not far from Kilmainham jail & Guinness Storehouse. The locale is full of character, and Mount Brown is a series of leafy little estates tucked in off the side of the road. It's one of Dublin 08's best-kept secrets! It's a 25 minute walk to Templebar area.

The house is in a quiet, suburban neighbourhood, about half way between the airport and the city centre. There are local shops, pubs, restaurants and takeaways 5 - 10 minutes away. It's 20-30 minutes by bus to both the City Centre and the Airport. It is a very safe neighbourhood and is safe for people travelling alone.
The local buses run from about 6:30 am until about 11:30 pm.
The last bus leaves the airport at 11:30 pm.

The house is only 10 mins walk to the sea.  Walking the pier in Dun Laoghaire is a lovely and local thing to do.  Of you are brave you can head to 40 Foot for a swim - it recently featured in Lonely Planets top swimming locations in the world - 20 mins walk away or 5 mins by car.  Lots of restaurants in Dun Laoghaire or Glasthule - depending which way you turn at the gate.  Cavistons in Glasthule is a wonderful foodie store with wonderful fresh produce - fruit, vegetables, farmhouse Irish cheeses, a wonderful array of fresh fish.  A great experience all round.  The People’s Park in Dun Laoghaire has a farmers market every Sunday which is also a must when here.

Smithfield is trendy, vibrant inner city area just north of the river Liffey. Almost everything you could wish to see is within walking distance such as supermarket, pharmacy, nice selection of food places, cinema, museum and more. Very quiet and peaceful in the evening, it's also a very safe area. Walking distance to city centre 10 min but if you prefer there is the luas tram at 2 stops from city centre.

We live in a quiet residential area with a local shop 5 minutes walk from the house. There is a lovely hidden gem of a cafe only 10 minutes walk away called Anderson's located on The Rise which we would highly recommend. Another favourite cafe of ours is called McMahon's which is a 20 minutes walk from our house. It's very close to The Botanic Gardens which are also worth checking out. The nearest park for a stroll is Albert College Park which is a 5 minute walk and is connected to the local University grounds. I would also recommend a new restaurant called Two Boys Brew in Phibsborough which you can get the bus to on the way into town. There is quite a famous old pub near our house (5 minute drive/30 minute walk) called The Gravediggers, located at the gates of Glasnevin cemetery. The cemetery is another historical tourist attraction. Phoenix Park is a beautiful place for a long walk and is a 15 minute drive away.
Numerous local coffee shops and places to grab food
Quartier très central, Smithfield, tout le centre peut se visiter à pied depuis notre logement.
The area of Camden street is a hip, lively and vibrant place. Great for local bars and cheap eats. A great place for anyone looking to see where real Dubliners go out!

Our house is right in the heart of the Village District, a hub of Dublin’s best food and bars, hugely popular with locals. Stoneybatter is an old historical area of Dublin built in part by the Guinness family at the turn of the 20th century to accommodate workers from the world famous brewery. The area has strong links to Dublin's Viking past reflected in its colourful Nordic street names. The surrounding borough's of Smithfield, Cabra, Broadstone, Phibsborough and the Four Courts formed a key battleground during the Easter 1916 Rising, an event which led to the formation of the modern Irish state and is enjoying its centenary celebration this year.

This is a very friendly, welcoming neighbourhood with an eclectic mix of young and old living in the community. It is the perfect place to base yourself as a visitor, while at the same time getting a flavour for daily life in this energetic and exciting city.

Stoneybatter village is often referred to as Dublin's bohemian quarter with its large choice of cafés, pubs, restaurants, museums and arthouse cinema.

Family oriented, quiet cul de sac.

Francis Street  is a really lovely quiet, safe and unique street, located in the antique quarter of Dublin. Within 2-5 minutes walking there are some excellent craft, design shops, antique shops (for which Francis Street is famous for), lovely churches including St Patrick's Cathedral and Christchurch and some of the best local pubs and music venues in Dublin,  The Guinness Storehouse is located within a short stroll of the apartment, and some of the local pubs on the street are known to serve the best pints of Guinness in all of Dublin. The Brazen Head pub which is the oldest pub in Dublin, is located within a very short walking distance from the apartment.

Our neighbourhood is in the heart of Dublin 1, beside the business district, and pretty much everything you need is within walking distance including The Convention Centre, light rail luas linking the city centre is 2 mins walk away. Rathmines has over 600 years of history. The Battle of Rathmines was fought in August 1649 during the Irish Confederate Wars. The battle facilitated the landing in Ireland of Oliver Cromwell and Cromwellian conquest of Ireland. For those interested in architecture there are two major churches. The Church of Mary Immaculate with its iconic copper done is one of the best known sights in Rathmines. The famous Cathal Brugha Barracks houses the Military Archives of Ireland.

If I wasn’t from there, Howth peninsula in north county Dublin would be on my bucket list of places to visit in Ireland. For generations it has witnessed many Irish marriage proposals on its beautiful cliffs! A stone’s throw from Dublin city but a holiday destination in its own right, Howth is a looped peninsula with stunning vistas out onto Lambay island, Slieve Gullion and the Mourne Mountains. Take one of the interestingly named circular walks (black linn, bog of frogs, cliff path and tramline loop) and in addition to the stunning scenery you may encounter kittiwakes, guillemots, razorbills and grey seals.
Take a break in the Summit Inn or finish your walk with well-deserved refreshments in the Bloody Stream (a pub that is built into the old railway station and is named after the blood that was spilled in the Norman defeat of the Vikings at Howth in the 12th century).

Skerries is a picturesque fishing village on the north coast of Dublin County. We have a local surf company that rents SUP boards and kayaks. There are (seasonal) boat trips available to Rockabill/Lambay Islands. We have a little Tourist office on Thomas Hand St. that can help you organise tours of the area. There are plenty of nice short, flat walks. The Mill offers a short tour and also has a gift shop and cafe. Ardgillan castle is only 10 minutes drive or 20 mins walk (via Ladies Stairs) walk away.

Skerries has many great award winning restaurants. Some of our favourites are Stoop Your Head, 5 Rock, Seasons, Olive and The 54. There are traditional music sessions in Joe Mays on a Sunday night and in the Snug on Thursday nights, Folk music in Nealons on Wednesdays and various bands in Raffs on Saturday nights.

Rathgar has a great selection of local gourmet produce available in Super Valu and in The Butler's Pantry. The 108 Bar has an extensive local and international craft beer selection as well as a few rare whiskeys. The Bottlers Bank is more traditional, with original fittings and fantastic character. Both pubs are a few mins walk from the apartment.

Rathmines is a short walk down the road where there are bakeries, cafes, restaurants and a swimming pool. The Blackbird is a new pub for a younger crowd, with old beds being transformed into tables and an eclectic selection of board games. Rody Bolanes has a more traditional style, with most of its furniture and decor moved from an authentic 18th century pub in Tipperary.

My neighbourhood is where the origins of the historical Dublin City began. Christchurch the largest Catholic Cathedral in town was built upon the original Viking settlements where Dublin City originated.
A trip to 'Dublinia' maps out how the City was during Viking times and their influence to this day.
Ironically at the bottom of St Patricks Street you will find St Patricks Cathedral, our other beautiful Cathedral looked over by the writer Dead Swift who was Dean of the Cathedral during the 1700's. Here you can take a walk in the adjoining park and have a coffee in it's pop up coffee shops.
A short distance from here is Grafton Street our main commercial high end shopping street.
The amazing thing about Dublin is that you can walk everywhere, its large enough to have everything a city needs but small enough for it all to be fabulously accessible by foot, if you like walking.

The area is known as The Liberties. It was the very first area of Dublin city to be built up outside of the original city walls, almost 1000 years ago. As such, the laws of the city did not apply, and residents were "at liberty" to do as they pleased!!
Unfortunately, the laws apply to everyone in the area nowadays, but The Liberties has a lovely mix of "old Dublin" and an element of gentrification which brings nice restaurants, pubs and coffee shops to an area just 15 minutes walk to Trinity College.

The Liberties is a hub of both Irish and international culture, with a range of attractions for all. The wider area of Dublin 8 is home to five of Ireland's top 20 visitor attractions, with the Guinness Storehouse alone accounting for 1.2 million annual visit. These house were built over 100 years ago to house the Guinness Factory workers.

IMMA is housed in the 17th-century Royal Hospital Kilmainham– a striking location for displaying modern art. Modelled o Les Invalides in Paris, it is arranged around a courtyard and the interior has long corridors running along series of modest interlocking rooms.

The original stables have been restored, extended and converted into artists' studios, and the museum runs an artist-in-residence programme.

The Liberties has a vibrant nightlife and hosts regular performances in theatres, bars, and music venues. Regular performances are held in these venues, serving local, citywide, and national populations.

Of course, Trinity College, Temple Bar, and the shopping area of Grafton Street are just a 10 to 15 minute stroll down through Dame Street passing the Olympia Theatre as you go.  Self hire Dublin bikes are available at Wood Quay, Christchurch Place, should you like to tour Dublin by bike.  In that case I would recommend a ride up to the Phoenix Park, one of the largest Public Parks in Europe and so beautiful, you might catch sight of a deer or a stag.  The Phoenix Park is about a 20 minutes walk, and if you like to get a run in on your break, you would certainly enjoy the sights here.

Killester/Clontarf is a great choice if you are looking for a peaceful residential area with plenty of green and open space. Ardgillan Castle is our nearest Park which is very peaceful and nice to go for a walk and has beautiful views of the Mourne Mountains. As well as the castle, the demesne features a walled and rose garden and has a café and childrens’ playground.

The north inner city of Dublin is a vibrant multicultural melting pot. This is living like a local.

You have everything at your doorstep in the city centre and there's an exciting mix of cultures and ideas to cater for every whim you might have.

This is an old traditional "working class" part of town. The houses are cosy and functional - all built in the 1920's. It's famous for the huge Croke Park stadium - the home of the GAA - which hosts 2 big concerts most years and of course many matches most weekends.

It's a very "studenty" part of town being very near to DCU and the Mater Hospital. This means there are plenty of good small restaurants and convenience stores all around.

For a pleasant walk I may recommend the Canal (up by the statue of Brendan Behan) or a great walk via Griffith Park to the Botanic Gardens and onwards to Glasnevin Cemetery.

Drumcondra (as the area is known) was the stomping ground of Bertie Ahern if you're interested in that sort of thing.

What's not to love about Dublin 8 these days! We are huge fans and hope that you enjoy this magical part of Dublin as much as we do. This area is diverse, hosting the museum of modern art (IMMA) in Kilmainham hospital, as well as the Guinness Brewery, Teelings Distillery, Saint Patrick's Cathedral, Christchurch Cathedral together with an array of coffee shops and pubs as well as Dublin's antique quarter on Francis Street. There are also some fabulous coffee shops and pubs. We would highly recommend coffee shops 'two pups' on Francis Street, 'Legit' on Meath Street and 'The Fumbally' on Clanbrassil Street. Our favourite local pub is Fallon's, on New Row Square.

House is nestled between the 2 central Dublin hamlets of Drumcondra and Phibsboro. Both are up and coming neighbourhoods with a mix of young professionals and families who have lived there for generations. The Botanic Gardens and historic Glasnevin Cemetery are a 30 minute walk away. Phoenix Park, the largest city park in Europe is a 40 min walk away or a 5 min bus journey. The house is located in Stoneybatter. The neighbourhood has plenty of of old school Dublin character but has been known as an "up-and-coming" part of the city for quite some time now. It is precisely this mixture which makes Stoneybatter appealing to locals and tourists alike.

Apart from the striking red brick artisan dwellings, the area is also known for the prominent Viking street names. For example, there is Viking Road, Olaf Road, Thor Place, Norseman Place, Ard Ri Road, Ostman Place & Sigurd Road. At the time of the Norman invasion, the Vikings, Ostmen or Austmenn (men of the East) as they called themselves, were exiled to the north of the Liffey where they founded the hamlet of Ostmenstown it what is now Stoneybatter.

The house is situated in one of the oldest and most historic areas in Dublin. The Liberties (Irish: Na Saoirsí or occasionally Na Libirtí) is an area in central Dublin, located to the southwest of the inner city. The area is traditionally associated with, market traders, local family owned businesses, as well as whiskey distilling, it is now also a centre of enterprise and commercial life in the heart of the city. Today the historic city quarter sits side by side with dynamic media and tech hubs and highly respected medical and educational centres.

Dublin 4, considered one of the more upper-class districts of the city, was initially developed by the Georgian gentry, who built the wide boulevards and red brick houses which remain to this day. As a consequence of their convenient location with relation to the Irish Houses of Parliament, many of the surrounding buildings are nowadays used as embassies, with the American embassy within 5 minute walk of the apartment.

More recently, the district has been bolstered further by the arrival of several of the worlds largest multinational tech companies, who have chosen Dublin 4 as the location of their European Headquarters. The house is situated in one of the oldest and most historic areas in Dublin. The Liberties (Irish: Na Saoirsí or occasionally Na Libirtí) is an area in central Dublin, located to the southwest of the inner city. The area is traditionally associated with, market traders, local family owned businesses, as well as whiskey distilling, it is now also a centre of enterprise and commercial life in the heart of the city. Today the historic city quarter sits side by side with dynamic media and tech hubs and highly respected medical and educational centres.

The house is situated in one of the oldest and most historic areas in Dublin. The Liberties (Irish: Na Saoirsí or occasionally Na Libirtí) is an area in central Dublin, located to the southwest of the inner city. The area is traditionally associated with, market traders, local family owned businesses, as well as whiskey distilling, it is now also a centre of enterprise and commercial life in the heart of the city. Today the historic city quarter sits side by side with dynamic media and tech hubs and highly respected medical and educational centres.

The Phoenix Park is right on your doorstep and is a must see. The park is steeped in history; it was originally formed back in the 1660’s as a Royal Hunting Park. In the opposite direction at the back of the apartment complex are The Irish National War Memorial Gardens. These gardens are dedicated the 49,400 Irish men who died during WW1. There is an abundance of flower gardens here and it’s a beautiful place to visit.

The neighbourhood, Portobello, is the epicentre of epicurean Dublin, housing some of Dublin’s finest restaurants and bars, and offering everything from haute cuisine to simple street fare. Everything is a short walk away.

My favourite spots:
•O'Donoghues - Built in 1789 as a grocery store and serving pints since 1934. A traditional Irish pub with live music. The Dubliners, Christy Moore and Phil Lynott have spent many a memorable night entertaining Dublin's music lovers in this bar.

•Grogans – a local pub in the heart of the city. A warm and friendly atmosphere that you would expect from your local, but with the lively buzz and intensity of an authentic Dublin city pub. If you choose to sit or stand outside you can people-watch with a warm toasty and the best Guinness in the world. Grogans is one of those places that time stands still and where the world passes by. Grogans is Liam Gallagher of Oasis favourite pub to visit when in Dublin.

The neighbourhood will forever be associated with The Easter Rising of 1916 - a highly significant moment in the history of the struggle for Irish independence. It's proximity to the centre has always given it prominence, but in the mid to late 20th century a lot of local industries closed down or moved out to out-of-town sites that could accommodate their growing businesses, leaving a lot of buildings vacated, so the local economy suffered as a result.

Fortunately the city & the government gave incentives for investment and since then a lot of traditional Georgian properties have been updated & restored, while apartments & student accommodation have been constructed on former industrial sites.

The history is reflected in the location of interactive multi-media exhibitions commemorating The Easter Rising (GPO less than 10 minutes walk) & the Famine/mass emigration of the 1840s (EPIC less than 20 minutes walk) in the area. More recently there has been a massive in

Ballsbridge is arguably Dublin's most exclusive address. Streets such as Shrewsbury Road and Ailesbury Road boast the highest real estate prices in Ireland with asking prices of up to €50 million for a single property. The area has traditionally been the home of the majority of foreign embassies and diplomatic representations in Dublin. It is not hard to see why the rich and powerful come to Ballsbridge: Originally developed in Victorian times, the streets are wide and tree lined and houses are substantial and set back in vast private grounds. Of all Dublin areas, Ballsbridge has the least built-up and most 'private' feel. Yet, despite the space and relative tranquility, Ballsbridge is only minutes away from the city centre.

Malahide is a picturesque coastal town located on a beautiful  estuary only 25 minutes from Dublin City Centre and 15 minutes from Dublin Airport. With 5 kilometers of stunning beaches, a Marina, immaculate parks and castle grounds within a 2 minute walk and 5 of the top 20 Irish golf courses within a 15 minute drive the location is unrivaled. Malahide boasts over 40 diverse restaurants and award winning bars, along with dozens of chic boutiques and coffee shops all are within a 2 minute walk. Howth is an idyllic fishing village on the northeast of Dublin and has been immortalised in James Joyce’s Ulysses. The grounds of 15th-century Howth Castle have rhododendron gardens and a transport museum with local trams. The 19th-century Martello Tower houses a vintage radio museum.  The medieval ruins of St. Mary’s Abbey lie nearby.  A clifftop trail has sweeping sea views, indeed H.G. Wells once remarked that Howth had "the finest views west of Naples".  Offshore, Ireland’s Eye is an island bird sanctuary with an ancient ruined church.  Walk around the working fishing village of Howth to explore the range of food on offer.  Enjoy the best traditional fish and chips in the city or sample some of the finest seafood cuisine all with the added perk of stunning coastal views.

I moved to the Liberties for its vibrant urban mix. The area has it all, from hip cafes (try Legit on Meath Street, Two Pups on Frances Street, or the famous Fumbally) to Meath Street's lively street market. There are many pubs from the traditional, to contemporary (drop into The Beer Market for craft beer) and of course the Guinness Storehouse. There are shops for groceries etc on Thomas Street, and antiques on Francis Street. Marlowe and Co, a fantastic bakery for pastries and sourdough/artisan breads about 10 minutes' walk away. You're less than 10 minutes' walk from the Liffey, 15 Minutes from the Irish Museum of Modern Art at Kilmainham, or from Temple Bar - the whole of central Dublin is within easy walking distance.

The cottage is just off the canal, a stones throw away from Leonard's Corner, an up and coming area which has everything you need: one of the nicest restaurants in Dublin (Bastible), a lovely local vintage pub, a gin bar, a supermarket, a butcher's, an Indian restaurant, a few lovely cafe's and much more. It is also a 15 minute walk from Portobello, Rathmines and Harold's Cross, three lovely neighbourhoods, which each have their own charm and are well worth a visit.

Just North of the River Liffey and a short walk from historic O'Connell Street, this is the very heart of the city centre and the perfect location for anyone wishing to explore the city by foot.

One of Dublin’s main shopping hubs is O'Connell Street (and its tributary, the ever-busy Henry Street), which culminates in a spearhead of excellent museums dotted around Parnell Square (most notably the Hugh Lane Gallery). To the west of here is the up-and-coming Smithfield and, further still, the vast Phoenix Park (also home to Dublin Zoo) while just across the bridge to the south is the formidable campus of Trinity College, with its ancient claim to fame in pride of place in the Old Library & Book of Kells.

You have everything at your doorstep in the city centre and there's an exciting mix of cultures and ideas to cater for every whim you might have.

You will be staying South of the river Liffey in the city centre, close to most attractions by foot, and with easy access to public transport. You’ll find yourself walking distance from Christchurch Cathedral, a magnificent structure and one of Dublin’s top tourist attractions. Dublin Castle, St Patrick's Cathedral and The Guinness Storehouse are also closeby landmarks worth visiting!

Once you’ve had your fill of historic wonders, you may wish to take a walk up Francis Street. Francis street is full to the brim of antique shops and bric a brac, for anyone who likes to discover old Irish hidden gems. At the other end of Francis Street you will arrive at a very trendy part of town, and should stop by to visit the Green Door Market to purchase fresh produce and delectable artisanal food. Nearby is the Fumbally Stables and Cafe, a local haunt for coffee lovers, sourdough bread bakers and farm-to-table enthusiasts. The Stables also hosts interesting courses, talks and yoga class

I really love Dublin 8 - it's the perfect mix of all the weird and wonderful things the city has to offer. It's chilled, it's lively, it's often gritty and it's home to tons of art, design and music studios.
It's a lovely piece of old Dublin, the neighbourhood having been constructed in 1923 on a field that was once used for drying and hanging the textiles of the cotton industry, hence the name, The Tenters. In some ways it feels like it's far away from the city, it's so calm. There's a great mix of people living in the area, from artists and actors to the typical Dublin 'aul wans', and plenty of funky cafes and proper old Dublin pubs just a short walk away. Though it's not quite in the centre of the action, everything you could need is a few minutes away.

Bray is the biggest town in County Wicklow.  It is known as the Gateway to the Garden of Ireland and is the longest established seaside town in Ireland. It is only 19km (12 miles) south of Dublin and is reached by DART, Train, Bus or the N11 road. There is a safe beach of sand and shingle to walk on and there is a spacious esplanade. The scene is dominated by Bray Head. The scenic Cliff Walk is on the eastern side of Bray Head continues along the cliff path towards Greystones offering walkers a feast of views on the way.

Wanton quirkiness, perennial liveliness and an endearing touch of shabbiness have always been part of Phibsboro’s innate appeal. It was where I wanted to live as a DCU student in the late nineties, instead of the gentler, more refined environs of Drumcondra where I was instead. Phibsborough was where the cool kids hung out, with an ice rink, a surfeit of charity shops and good pubs like The Hut, where the Johnny Cash Appreciation Society were in situ on a Sunday night. And then there was McGowan’s, where young love was almost certainly guaranteed to bloom, especially after a few drinks.
Fast forward to now and Phibsboro (or Phibsborough – both spellings are considered perfectly acceptable) retains much of the charm that made it so attractive back then. Location wise, it’s pretty much perfect, being a few minutes from the city centre but also close to the perennially wanderable likes of GLASNEVIN CEMETERY and the BOTANICAL GARDENS. Clontarf (Cluain Tarbh), Co. Dublin, is a seaside suburb on the Dublin - Howth road. It is one stop on the DART from the city centre, has a cosy village atmosphere and most roads lead down to the sea. Some of the best roads back on to St. Anne's Park, with its award-winning rose garden. In 550 A.D. a church was founded on Castle avenue by St. Comgall of Bangor; nothing is known of its history. Clontarf is the celebrated as the place of Brain Boru's great victory over Leinster and Norse Dublin, Good Friday, 1014 A.D., where St. Lawrence Road stands today. Clontarf was a fishing village and a popular seabathing resort for city people around the time when the Vernon family were the largest land-owners in Clontarf. Why not cross over to Bull island for a picnic, via the road bridge, or go for a swim on Dollymount strand?

I really love Dublin 8 - it's the perfect mix of all the weird and wonderful things the city has to offer. It's chilled, it's lively, it's often gritty and it's home to tons of art, design and music studios.
It's a lovely piece of old Dublin, the neighbourhood having been constructed in 1923 on a field that was once used for drying and hanging the textiles of the cotton industry, hence the name, The Tenters. In some ways it feels like it's far away from the city, it's so calm. There's a great mix of people living in the area, from artists and actors to the typical Dublin 'aul wans', a flea market around the corner and plenty of funky cafes and proper old Dublin pubs just a short walk away. Though it's not quite in the centre of the action, everything you could need is a few minutes away.

Dublin 4 is a historic postal district of Dublin, Ireland including Baggot Street Upper and the suburbs of Ballsbridge, Donnybrook, Irishtown, Merrion, Ringsend (including South Lotts and parts of Grand Canal Dock) and Sandymount, on the South side of Dublin. Most of the area was known as Pembroke Township until 1930 when it was absorbed by the City and County Borough of Dublin. Under Ireland's Eircode system the postcode is now rendered D04.

The headquarters of the national broadcaster RTÉ, the RDS, Merrion Centre, University College Dublin, Aviva Stadium, Google and a number of foreign embassies to Ireland are all located in Dublin 4.

Ballsbridge is on the south side of the city. It has been the urban retreat of choice for Dublin's wealthy citizens since the 19th century. Ringsend is a south side inner suburb of Dublin, Ireland. It is located on the south bank of the River Liffey and is about two kilometres east of the city centre. Tucked away to the south of Dublin‘s River Liffey and up against the Irish Sea, Ringsend is a stronghold of the traditional Dubliner, though it has developed fast in recent years. A previously largely working-class reputation has been set aside with an influx of the likes of Google, Facebook and the improved national football stadium (the Aviva) moving in just down the road.

The house is situated in one of the oldest and most historic areas in Dublin. The Liberties (Irish: Na Saoirsí or occasionally Na Libirtí) is an area in central Dublin, located to the southwest of the inner city. The area is traditionally associated with, market traders, local family owned businesses, as well as whiskey distilling, it is now also a centre of enterprise and commercial life in the heart of the city. Today the historic city quarter sits side by side with dynamic media and tech hubs and highly respected medical and educational centres.

Baggot Street is known for its many pubs, and is home to the "Baggot Street Mile", a pub crawl which consists of having a pint in every pub on both Upper and Lower Baggot Street and some of the adjoining streets, usually at least twelve pubs in number. Depending on the variation, the Mile usually starts at the Den (at the Landsdowne Hotel, actually on Pembroke Road) and ends at the Pembroke (on Pembroke Street, now closed), O'Donoghues (Merrion Row) or The Horseshoe Bar (at the Shelbourne Hotel, St. Stephen's Green).  The Baggot Street Mile is a traditional route for the Twelve Pubs of Christmas pub crawl

Nicknamed “Silicon Docks,” this once-neglected and rundown part of the city is now home to a plethora of high-tech, multi-national companies, including Google, Facebook, Twitter, LinkedIn, AirBnB and many more. About 15 years ago, an urban renewal project renovated the derelict houses and warehouses overlooking the water and today it is a stunning neighborhood full of hipster shops, trendy eateries, the Grand Canal Theater and modern, waterfront apartments. Running along the River Liffey, the area is an enclosed harbour where the Grand Canal joins the river. A canal history outlines the various stages of the area in a high-tech display at the floating Waterways Ireland Visitor Center and visitors into windsports will love the kayaking and windsurfing.

Although Dublin is known for its seemingly endless sprawling suburbs, the city center is relatively small and contains many of the city’s attractions, including most of the historical sights, nightlife venues, shops and cultural attractions. Most people agree that the O’Connell Bridge is the direct heart of the city center and this relatively small metropolis has an old-world charm thanks to its narrow, winding streets and old buildings, few of which are taller than four stories.
In the heart of the city you’ll find a delightful mix of generally laid-back with a small dose of chaos. The center is home to the newest ideas, latest designs, trendies startups and revolutionary dining. A diverse mix of people call Dublin home and sights within the centre that you won’t want to miss include Trinity College, The Hugh Lane Gallery, The Science Gallery, two of the city’s most spectacular parks, Dublin Castle, and the main shopping mile on Grafton Street.

The oldest settled area of Dublin, Chapelizod still feels like a village, bordered by the River Liffey and the Park and with a strong sense of community. What makes it really special is the largest walled park in Europe as your back garden with entrance 50 m away and the wandering deer always close by. To the West are Carton and Castletown Houses and to the East are the Guinness Brewery, IMMA and the neighbouring river Liffey.

When the sun shines in Dublin, it lights up the streets to reveal a truly beautiful city. You'll find Generator Dublin in the hip Smithfield neighbourhood; adjacent to the Jameson Distillery and just a short walk from Temple Bar. It’s ideal for a girls’ or boys’ weekend away – especially if you’re after a more luxurious budget hotel experience in Dublin.

The Liberties is a traditional working class Dublin neighbourhood that is currently going through a process of gentrification with the opening of trendy cafes and pubs, hotels and student residences in the area. It hosts the National College of Arts and Design, the Digital Hub, co-working spaces and several cultural attractions, like the Guinness Storehouse, Saint Patrick's Cathedral (surrounded by a lovely park), Christchurch Cathedral, Marsh Library, the Museum of Modern Art, the Kilmainham Gaol Museum and no less than three whiskey distilleries.
There are many local shops (butcher's, fishmonger's, grocer's, bakery as well as pharmacies, Lidl, Tesco and Spar).
It's only 15 minutes walk from the city centre and its many other museums and attractions.

Harolds Cross is a great neighbourhood, full of cool cafes, a couple of really excellent restaurants and several local shops and services. Historic Harolds Cross park is a lovely green oasis nearby and it has a great childrens' playground. The villages of Rathmines and Rathgar are within an easy walk and the city centre is easily reached by many bus routes.

Dublin 4 is a historic postal district of Dublin, Ireland including Baggot Street Upper and the suburbs of Ballsbridge, Donnybrook, Irishtown, Merrion, Ringsend (including South Lotts and parts of Grand Canal Dock) and Sandymount, on the South side of Dublin. Most of the area was known as Pembroke Township until 1930 when it was absorbed by the City and County Borough of Dublin. Under Ireland's Eircode system the postcode is now rendered D04.

The headquarters of the national broadcaster RTÉ, the RDS, Merrion Centre, University College Dublin, Aviva Stadium, Google and a number of foreign embassies to Ireland are all located in Dublin 4.

Ballsbridge is on the south side of the city. It has been the urban retreat of choice for Dublin's wealthy citizens since the 19th century. With its posh airs and exclusive residences, Ballsbridge is the home to foreign embassies, several rugby clubs and the Royal Dublin Society with its annual horse show. Of all Dublin areas, Ballsbridge has the least built-up and most 'private' feel. Yet, despite the space and relative tranquility, Ballsbridge is only minutes away from the city centre.

Chapelizod is a very historic village, the name means "Iseult's Chapel" and is believed to be linked to the story of Princess Iseult/Isolde from the Arthurian legend of Tristan and Isolde. The church of St Laurence is very beautiful, with its 14th-century bell tower. The village features in some of James Joyce's short stories as well as his novel Finnegan's Wake.
