Stonybatter is small neighbourhood in Dublin City Centre. The following blurb is from Timeout magazine which included Stonybatter in its 'Top 50' of coolest neighbourhoods in the world.

"This area feels like its own world, a quirky little fortress of cool in the heart of the city. Dubliners who’ve lived here their whole lives now mingle with trendy newcomers clambering to rent one of its cute little cottages. And on sunny days, locals and visitors alike perch by their doorways to catch some rays (most often over a glass of wine).

Happily, the ’Batter is also fast becoming one of Dublin’s most exciting foodie areas, with neighbourhood restaurants luring gourmands from all over. Whether it’s the gooey, spreadable scalda ’nduja in Grano or the vegan cheese tower at *Beo Wine Bar – yep, you heard us – you can certainly see why"

*the Beo bar is now closed and is now a tapas restaurant which is across the street from our property

Stay in Dublin’s beating heart. Nestled between some of Dublin’s best pubs and two iconic cathedrals, Christchurch is where old Dublin meets new. On one side you have Temple bar and Grafton street with boutique shops and hip eateries. On the other there’s the eclectic Liberties neighbourhood where craft beer bars and event spaces rub up next to traditional family businesses and red brick cottages.

The apartment is perfectly located for exploring the city; all of the city's cultural institutions are within walking distance and the transport connections are excellent

NORTHSIDE CULTURAL ATTRACTIONS
The North side of Parnell Square (10 min walk) is home to the city's Hugh Lane Gallery of Modern Art; we share a significant collection of Impressionist painting with the Tate Gallery in London, part of the Hugh Lane Bequest, which is rotated in seven-year cycles. Next door is the Writer's Centre, and next door again, is the Writer's Museum, with a Michelin-starred restaurant in the basement, the amazing Chapter One. Down on the East side of Parnell Square is the beautiful jewel-box that is the Gate Theatre - part of the 18th-century entertainment complex established by the entrepreneurial Dr. Bartholomew, to help support his new Rotunda Maternity Hospital (the oldest purpose-built such hospital in the world, and still delivering babies on a daily basis, 270 years later (

Located between the M11 to the North, the sea to the East and Wicklow to the South, Shankill is a unique large village in South County Dublin. It lacks nothing in infrastructure including its access to Rail, Luas, Bus routes and the Motorway and has an extensive network of Sports Clubs and facilities including GAA, Soccer, Tennis, and Golf (3 Clubs within 1 ½ miles). There is a expansive Park which includes playing pitches, playgrounds, and walkways is a short walking distance away. The Village Centre provides for every requirement and offers plenty of choice with boutique shops, a bakery, and a gastropub, to name but a few. Schools, and the local St. Columcilles Hospital are of excellent quality and provide for almost all needs. The Village has a nice tranquillity feel to it and friendly atmosphere.

Our house is set in a quiet estate, within walking distance of Swords. There are some shops and amenities approximately 5 minutes walk away including:
- Large supermarket (Dunnes Stores & Lidl)
- Hairdresser and Beautician
- Barber
- Pharmacy
- Florist
- Take Away Chip Shop
- Bus Stop (serving a number of stops including Dublin Airport and City Center)

Swords town is 1.5km away, taking about 15-20 mins to walk to it. Here there is a lively and busy atmosphere with facilities including:
- Pavillions Shopping Center (5 min Drive)
- Restaurants
- Bars
- Night Clubs
- Public Park & Playground
- Gym
- Swords Castle
- Doctor
- Dentist

Tayto Park (30 min Drive)

Dublin Zoo (30 min Drive)

Malahide Castle & Gardens (12 Min Drive)

Dublin Airport (12 min Drive)

Portmarnock Beach (20 min Drive)

In this location, the chances are you won’t see so much of the room as you’ll be out exploring! The room is located just across the road from St. Michan's Church. Temple Bar is a busy riverside neighborhood, spreading over cobbled pedestrian lanes. Crowded pubs host live folk music and DJ sets, and typically Irish restaurants serve international and Irish cuisine. It is a 10-minute walk and Dublin castle is a similar distance. Jervis Shopping center is within a 12-minutes walk, where you can find a pharmacy, supermarkets, cell phone repair shops and more. You can also get there by taking the red Luas line just one stop after Four Courts Luas stop. In fact, most of Dublin’s tourist attractions are easily walkable from here. Portobello is where its at for Dublin's best restaurants and cafes. there is too many mention. we have a Michelin star restaurants in Locks and Bastible (Locks s meters away from the front door).
The house is 12 mins walk from St Stephens green.

A 6 minute walk from St Patricks Cathedral
A 10 minute walk to the Guiness Storehouse
A 10 minute walk from Temple Bar
A 12 minute walk to Dublin Castle
A 16 minute walk from Jameson Distillery
A 14 minute walk to St Stephens green
A 7 minute walk to Energie fitness Gym
Simply an outstanding location, sea views, beach walks and public parks. Gastronomic delight with access to numerous dining options. All within a very short walking distance.

A lovely well established area… so near everything you need for a wonderful stay. Our home is in a small cul de sac so it’s pretty quiet.
We are minutes away from supermarkets, pharmacy, doctor and various takeaway food shops. We are also very close to buses which take you to Dublin City centre in 35 mins. Alternatively you can take the DART, the light rail into town , takes 30 minutes, or travel both north or south to discover all the beautiful little villages along the coast.


Town
Very friendly neighbours

Cottage is located within walking distance of the Boherbreena reservoir walk and new local coffee shack. local walking trails include  Seefin, Seefinigan and Corrig trail, old bog road to Kippure, Kippure via loch Bray trail to include only a few.

Dalkey village is a 5 minute walk away and has lots of shops, restaurants and pubs to choose from. Other local landmarks that are within walking distance include Killiney Hill, Killiney Beach, Coliemore Harbour & Dublin's famous baths - the Forty Foot.

Enjoy village life, with pubs, restaurants and the famous Powerscourt Estate just walking distance away.  There are loads of local walks by riverside and up onto the hills toward the famous Wicklow Way walking trail. Enniskerry is known as the Gateway to County Wicklow (the garden county). You can drive for 100 miles across the spectacular Wicklow mountains and never meet a traffic light. If you are a cycling enthusiast, then Enniskerry is a mecca for road and mountain biking. Golf courses are numerous in Wicklow and sea swimming is a short drive away. Whatever type of holiday you are after, we will be glad to pass on our local knowledge

Upper Baggot street is a charming street with many businesses. You will find 2 grocery stores, pubs, restaurants, pharmacies, and more within 5 minutes of the apartment.
Herbert park is about 10 minutes away, as well as Aviva Stadium. It will take you about 20 minutes to get downtown, or even less if you catch the bus.

Amazing, you have one of the best coffee shops on your doorstep, the tranquility of the River Dodder and the walks along it, fantastic restaurants in Ranelagh and Rathmines just 15 mins away and the city centre 25 mins walk / 7 mins drive. Also Irelands biggest shopping centre Dundrum SC is just 10mins drive away and can be access on loads of bus routes that pass on the main road outside the development. The beach of Sandymount Strand is 12 mins drive away practically the same time on a bicycle.

Please note!!! This is not a city centre location!!!
The beautiful suburb of Dundrum 15 minutes by car to the city, sea or mountains.The award winning Dundrum Town Centre is 10 minutes walk! Green Luas station 10/15 minutes walk .

Drumcondra is one of the older inner residential suburbs in north Dublin, with street built before some of its neighbours were even a twinkle in a city planner’s eye.
It stretches north from the Royal Canal on either side of N1, petering into Whitehall somewhere around Griffith Avenue. To the west are redbrickes of Glasnevin; to the east, Fairview and Marino.
Drumcondra is mostly quite, friendly and safe. It’s breched neatly between urban and suburban. Plus the last ten years or so have seen renewed influx of small independent businesses that are now like a community feel to the main road. It has own market and all.
This road is the way to the airport. It’s very handy to and from the airport, town, M1, M50, Croke Park and for anywhere along the railway line heading west.

Basically transport links are a serious plus.

The neighbourhood is quiet and safe. The house is surrounded by the beautiful Kilruddery Estate, Bray Head and Sugarloaf mountains. The famous Bray to Greystones cliff walk is only 10 minutes walk away. There are multiple places to eat in Bray and a range of pubs, restaurants are to be found on Bray's promenade.

The neighbourhood is residential, just off 2 main streets in Skerries.  Walkable to everything in the town, and approx. 10 mins from the train station.  Bus routes to city centre from the end of the street.
Vibrant and lively, good base to explore city ,  good few popular parks and canals around

Very nice and safe area in the heart of Dublin just in front of Liffey river.

In walking distance to Temple bar area, Trinity College, Molly Malone Statue, Dublin Castle, The Brazen Head, Phoenix park, Guiness Storehouse, Jameson distillery, Teeling distillery, National Museum of Ireland, Christ church cathedral, St. Patrick’s cathedral and many more.

In very near by area you have and options of grocery shops, fast food shops, restaurants, bars and off license.

Also you have a variation of public transport from very near by.

Located in Smithfield and Stoneybatter, the flat is close to many cafes, bars, and restaurants. You may buy groceries at the nearby convenience store and supermarket if you decide on a home-cooked meal. There’s even a pharmacy and clinic within walking distance in case of emergencies. Walking distance to the Jameson whiskey distillery and local farmers' markets on the weekend.
Quiet residential street in the heart of Dublin’s leafy Ballsbridge area.
Malahide is an up market unique Irish seaside village, yet only 15 minutes from the airport and a quick 20 minute fast train trip into the city of Dublin
Quite residential area beside a beautiful park and 20min walk to the sea. Plenty of restaurants, pubs and cafés close by

This property is located minutes away from Dublin city centre,  with vibrant local cafes and places to eat, the city centre and of course major universities including BIMM, National College of Art & Design, Royal College Of Surgeons and Trinity College

This unique neighbourhood has great cafes, bars and restaurants, parks and museums, including Ireland’s most famous historic prison - Kilmainham Gaol.
The Hilton hotel, which is next to the apartment complex has a lovely gym/pool/jacuzzi and sauna.
Dublin Bikes are directly across the road, which you can use to see the sites. The Dublin Hop On, Hop Off bus is also directly across the road, so you won’t be short of things to do while you stay ;)

The property is centrally located with walking distance to Dublin City Centre. The building benefits from an excellent location, superb transport links, and a sociable, relaxed atmosphere - everything you need for the perfect home.

8 minute stroll to Grocery Stores Aldi, Lidl and Tesco Express; 10 minute stroll to Henry Street Shopping District where you can find Arnotts Department Store and high street brands like M&S, H&M, Zara. Close to Garden of Remembrance, GPO and easily accessible Public Transport network.
As close to Dublin’s universities as it is to the city’s best bars, restaurants and shops, this is the perfect place to stay if you are looking to explore Dublin.

Blackrock is a great town full of amenities from cafes to beauty salons and is also home to Dublin's oldest market. We are a 10 min walk to the 2 shopping centres in Blackrock. Another 2 minutes brings you into the town where the DART (train) station is located.

The house is a the main road leading to Blackrock Park by the sea and the DART station. Over the bridge of the DART station is Blackrock swimming area. 2km south along the coast (a lovely walk, short cycle or 1 DART stop) brings you to Seapoint a very popular tidal beach and swimming spot with picturesque Monkstown village adjacent full of restaurants and cafes. Further south is Dun Laoghaire lined with boats. A walk on the pier is a must do followed by a meal out.

In the opposite direction the DART brings you into the city centre in 15mins.

YOU ARE IN THE BEST LOCATION IN DUBLIN ENJOY YOUR SELF :-), ITS A 3 BED APT WITH 3 DOUBLE BEDS AND THERE IS AN DOUBLE SOFA BED THAT CAN SLEEP 2 PEOPLE.There is pre pay power so you can top up on line at prepaypower or you can top up in a shop just 5 mins from apt or i can  ask my cleaner to top up for you
Howth

This is an old part of Dublin with traditional style buildings. There are shops located directly across the street, along with Cafes, restaurants and pubs. It is a good central location with access to many local tourist attractions and the city center for shopping only 10 minutes away by bus.

There is a wonderful little cafe called the Limetree and the Dublin food coop are right outside my apartment building. Across the road you will find historic Kilmainham Gaol and The Patriot pub, which is a great place to have a drink and meet the locals. Right next to it is The Irish Museum of Modern Art, which has a lovely cafe and in the court yard at certain times there are people selling delicious pancakes, crepes and coffee
Quiet, calm lovely bird song and rustling leaves,5 min walk from big supermarket. Bus stop near by,1 min.

House is located in a Architectural Conservation Area & is a protected structure; 2 acre landscaped park on our doorstep open daily from 10am to 8pm, perfect for picnics or leisurely strolls; Close to local shops, cafés and pubs in the popular Ranelagh Village and just 10 minute walk to St Stephen's Green/Dublin City Centre;
Next to Hanover Medical center
Quiet, pleasant, residential  area. Close to amenities.

Howth is a beautiful fishing village which offers amazing amenities. Everything is within walking distance from our house which includes an array of restaurants and bars, stunning cliff walks, access to local beachs's, the piers and woodlands.
There are local tours where we recommend you go on an e-BIKE or walking adventure to make the most of your trip! Visits to Ireland Eye Island are also available by boat from Howth Pier.

The house is in the heart of trendy Dublin 8, 5 minutes from the canal. There are many cafes and bars within a ten minute radius (Noshington, Headline Bar, MVP, Little Bird, Daddy's, the Circular, Baste, Locks and many many more)

The house is ideally located, with access to a sandy beach 200m from the door. From here you can walk into Howth or further on to burrow beach if the sea is far enough out. At high tide the beach is largely inaccessible so you may have it all to yourself!

Howth is a gorgeous spot, the village is famous for its seafood restaurants and there is a lovely buzz about the place with many people sitting outside enjoying food and a glass of wine. There are a couple of small museums, a playground and some boutique shops. There are often lots of visitors out walking the pier with a coffee and soaking up the views.

For walking fans the coastline offers a varied mix of cliffs, pebbly beaches and lots of sand, plus there are nice treks through old woods in the middle of the peninsula to summits with views over many counties (and on a good day you can even see Wales!)

There are a variety of water sports on offer - kayaking, yachting, diving, stand up paddle board....

*The Neighbourhood*
If you are looking to stay in a great location close to all that Dublin has to offer you then you have found the right place!!

- Dominick Luas stop - downstairs
- iLac Shopping Centre - downstairs
- Air couch / Airlink 747 - 3 mins walk
- The Spire - 5 mins walk
- Ha'penny Bridge - 10 mins walk
- Main High streets - O'Connell / Henry St - 3 mins walk
- Temple Bar - 10 mins walk

Vibrant and lively as we are very close to centre
Drumcondra train station few mins away
Bus stop to airport nearly at doorstep
Insomnia and subway nearby
Quiet rural area near Dublin city with fantastic hiking, cycling, ziplining, cafe and pub and access to the Wicklow Way, Tibradden mountain, Massy's woods and the Hellfire Club.
The neighborhood is not on the main road therefore is super quiet and great for resting and working in peace
This apartment is located in the lovely Mount Brown area of Dublin, which is in the city center. It is located close to museums, gardens, the zoo, restaurants, bars, and many other attractions.

House is 1 min walk from portmarnock village and its bustling cafes and shops.
1 min walk from bus stop serving city centre and malahide.
15 mins drive from Dublin Airport
10 mins walk from the beach.
15 mins from the dart.
15 min walk from both golf clubs.
5 min drive to Malahide Town.
10 mins drive to Howth.

The house is located on the South side of the city (South of the Liffey), in The Liberties, one of Dublin's most historic working-class neighborhoods, the area is traditionally associated with the River Poddle, market traders and local family-owned businesses, as well as the Guinness brewery, whiskey distilling, and, historically, the textiles industry and tenement housing.

After the dissolution of the monasteries by Henry VIII the liberties of Thomas Court and Donore was granted to William Brabazon, ancestor of the Earls of Meath.[6] In 1579 the city of Dublin claimed the abbey to be within the jurisdiction and liberty of the city, but they lost their case. From then on, the head of the liberty was the Earl of Meath. The family lent its name to places and streets in the district e.g. the Meath Market, the Meath Hospital and Meath Street. They also named Brabazon Row, Brabazon Street and Ardee Street (they were Barons Ardee since 1616).

The Liberties holds a range

Ballsbridge is on the south side of the city. It has been the urban retreat of choice for Dublin's wealthy citizens since the 19th century. With its posh airs and exclusive residences, Ballsbridge is the home to foreign embassies, several rugby clubs and the Royal Dublin Society with its annual horse show. Of all Dublin areas, Ballsbridge has the least built-up and most 'private' feel. Yet, despite the space and relative tranquility, Ballsbridge is only minutes away from the city centre.

Brightly painted villas, palm trees and townland parks greet visitors to Dún Laoghaire, an elegant port town just 13km from Dublin’s city centre. Popular with holiday makers since Victorian times, its appeal is timeless. Try your hand at sailing, take a dip in the sea, visit a museum, and top it all off with a 99 ice-cream cone on the pier.
Breathe in the sea air and watch the world go by as you stroll along Dún Laoghaire’s mile-long East Pier Walk. You’ll pass the beautiful Victorian bandstand as fishing boats and yachts sail quietly in and out of the harbour. Another recommended spot is The People’s Park. Created as a formal Victorian garden, this scenic space is enclosed by wrought iron railings, inside of which you’ll find beautifully landscaped lawns and bright flowers. Visit on a Sunday to sample the delights of Dún Laoghaire’s food and craft market.
You’ll be spoiled for choice when it comes to planning your Dún Laoghaire day trips. Anyone with even a passing interest

Fairview has been a part of suburban Dublin since the 1800s. In the beginning it was a refuge for well-off people seeking solace from the bustling city. The area originally bore the same name as neighbouring Ballybough. But in 1856 a church was dedicated to Our Lady of Fair View, giving the surrounding area the name used today.

Walk through Fairview and you’ll feel its unique vibe. It’s like a cross between the Liberties and Clontarf. Trendy bars and eateries sit comfortably alongside hardware stores and charity shops that have been here for years. Families who have been in the area for generations live happily alongside a metropolitan mix of young professionals.

The centre of Dublin has a very organic feel to it, with its winding, narrow streets and low buildings. There is only one grand avenue in the centre and that is O'Connell Street. The rest of the streets is much more human in scale. Few buildings in the city centre are more than four stories high and an appealing mix of 18th century Georgian and 19th century Victorian styles dominates most streets in the centre. Life in Dublin's city centre is charming, slightly chaotic and fairly laid back.

Dublin's Hub
Dublin City CentreDublin has a hub and spokes structure, with the centre as the hub and outlying areas as the spokes. Because of the relatively small size of Dublin, most fresh impulses and ideas start in the centre to reach the biggest possible audience. New shops, bars and nightclubs invariably operate from a city centre location and there are still enough up and coming areas waiting to be discovered, which keeps rents low for innovative start-ups. The Silicon Docks are a fast changing yet very historic area of Dublin.  Centrally located with many wonderful pubs, restaurants and independent stores the area has in recent years become the European hub of the technology multinationals. The Royal Canal passes along the northern boundary, separating Phibsborough from Glasnevin. Below the fifth lock, east of Crossguns Bridge, the Broadstone Harbour city markets-bound main branch of the canal ran south, to the now paved over the harbour. The filled-in former mainline is now covered by a linear park and the adjacent road is called the Royal Canal Bank. It consists of a variety of homes from multiple periods, some dating from the 1750s. The canal's current mainline runs south-east to Spencer Dock at the North Wall. The “parkway” passes Mountjoy Gaol, under Blacqueire Bridge, along the high banked eastern side of Phibsborough Road. Originally the Foster Aqueduct carried the mainline canal over the Phibsborough Road to the harbour terminus which sat directly opposite the King's Inns at Constitution Hill.[6]

The Silicon Docks are a fast changing yet very historic area of Dublin.  Centrally located with many wonderful pubs, restaurants and independent stores, the area has in recent years become a vibrant mix of long time resident friendly Dubliners and a diverse group of international residents working primarily in international technology or finance multinationals.  The area’s transformation is typified by the skyline of the Bolands Quay development, which visible from the floor -to-ceiling windows in the living room.   It was a large working mill for many decades and after a multi year redevelopment has now been relaunched as Google’s EMEA headquarters.

Dublin 8 - according to Time Out

“Dublin 8 captures the essence and charm of the Irish capital to a tee’. Over the past year, the area has seen a wealth of positive changes: Lucky’s pub has been transformed into a cultural hotspot with excellent rotating exhibitions, while Pearse Lyons has reintroduced tours of its church distillery. Green spaces like the War Memorial Gardens or Phoenix Park mean you can twin a day vintage shopping with something more outdoorsy – or you can head straight to MVP for a pint.

Sounds like a pretty dreamy part of the city, right? If you’re local, you may well have discovered the joys of Dublin 8 already. But for everyone else: add it to your bucket list ASAP.”

Courtesy of https://www.timeout.com/news/dublin-8-has-been-named-one-of-the-worlds-coolest-neighbourhoods-heres-why-100621

Dublin 1 is north inner city and is separated from Dublin 2 by the river Liffey. The area is home to O'Connell Street, Henry Street, Jervis Street, the Irish Financial Services Centre (IFSC), the Docklands, Parnell Street, Busarus, Connolly Station, the Customs House and the north city quays. Within Dublin 1 is one of the City’s most famous streets, O’Connell Street, on which the famous Dublin spike was built. Officially titled ‘The Monument of Light’ Dublin it is referred to by local Dubliners as the Spike. Excellent shopping can be found on and round O’Connell Street on streets such as Henry Street which is home to the Iliac and Jervis street shopping centre. Most of Dublin city centre is within a short walk of anywhere in Dublin 1. However the area has great transport links. The immediate area has a number of multi-storey car-parks and is well served by public transport in the form of Dublin Bus, Irish Rail from Connelly Station and the Red Luas line. Living on "the quays" (the walled river banks through the centre of Dublin) at Smithfield has been a joy since I moved to Dublin from Galway after university.

This is exactly where the original crossing place of the river Liffey grew into the town we call Dublin. Across the river is the Brazen Head, Ireland's oldest pub, while the Jameson whiskey distillery is almost next door.

Smithfield Square is outside our gate, with its artisan cafes and many restaurants, and when the breeze blows the right direction, you can smell the malt/coffee scent of Guinness barley being roasted, or hear the bells of Christchurch Cathedral.

Even from the window of your bright riverfront bedroom you can watch swans glide past, see a stork fishing from the Quay wall below, or, if you're lucky, see our seal (!!) swim past as the tide turns and he gets the opportunity to catch some freshwater fish!

Barrow Street, just off Sheridan Square, is a typical Greenwich Village street. Each house represents a layer of the Village's special architecture and history. A few of the buildings are a bit bedraggled; others are noble, and some are both.

In the late 18th century the western part of Greenwich Village, including what is now Barrow Street, was dotted with large estates. One of them, Richmond Hill, near what are now Charlton and Varick Streets, was owned for several years by Aaron Burr -- around the time of the 1804 duel in which he killed Alexander Hamilton.

Barrow Street may have been named for Thomas Barrow, an artist, but it is unclear when this part of the street got its name. The oldest remaining house on the street is No. 25, built in 1826. Other houses followed, and by 1850 the street was almost completely built up.

It is a historic area full of great cafes, pubs and local amenities. Walk to the world famous Guinness factory, Jameson Distillery and the largest walked park in Europe! Our house is located in the seaside town of Portmarnock, adjacent to Malahide.
We are a 20 minute drive from the airport, and have a good bus connection with Dublin city. The H2 bus goes directly to town, and the bus stop is a 5 minute walk away. The No 42 bus also stops here, and will bring you to Malahide train station or in to town.
Portmarnock has a fabulous 5km beach...the Velvet Strand.... which is a 10 minute walk away. From the beach you can enjoy stunning views of Howth, Ireland's Eye and Lambay Island. There is also a beautiful coastal walk between Portmarnock and Malahide and a lovely looped walk.
Portmarnock has some nice restaurants ,a pub and 2 hotels.. Neighbouring Malahide has a host of restaurants and pubs, and boasts a very vibrant night life. Malahide Castle is also close by.

There are two golf courses in Portmarnock, and good access to several others in the vicinity.
